{"title_page": "Push technology", "text_new": "{{tone|date=January 2019}}\n'''Push notifications'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pushmaze.com/what-is-push-notifications/|title=What is push notifications & How do push notifications work?|website=www.pushmaze.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-25|date=2018-09-22}}</ref> are small messages that can reach audiences anywhere and anytime. While pop-ups appear only when audiences are on the site they belong to, push messages are independent of sites. They are associated with web browsers and apps. \n\n'''Push technology''', or '''server push''', is a style of [[Internet]]-based communication where the request for a given transaction is initiated by the publisher or central [[server (computing)|server]]. It is contrasted with [[pull technology|pull]]/get, where the request for the transmission of information is initiated by the receiver or [[client (computing)|client]].\n\nPush services are often based on information preferences expressed in advance. This is called a [[publish/subscribe]] model. A client \"subscribes\" to various information \"channels\" provided by a server; whenever new content is available on one of those channels, the server pushes that information out to the client.\n\nPush is sometimes emulated with a [[polling (computer science)|polling]] technique, particularly under circumstances where a real push is not possible, such as sites with security policies that require rejection of incoming HTTP/S requests.\n\n== General use ==\n[[Synchronous conferencing]] and [[instant messaging]] are typical examples of push services. Chat messages and sometimes [[Computer file|files]] are pushed to the user as soon as they are received by the messaging service. Both decentralised [[peer-to-peer]] programs (such as [[WASTE]]) and centralised programs (such as [[Internet Relay Chat|IRC]] or [[Extensible Messaging and Presence Protocol|XMPP]]) allow pushing files, which means the sender initiates the data transfer rather than the recipient.\n\n[[Email]] may also be a push system: [[SMTP]] is a push protocol (see [[Push e-mail]]). However, the last step\u2014from mail server to desktop computer\u2014typically uses a pull protocol like [[POP3]] or [[IMAP]]. Modern e-mail clients make this step seem instantaneous by repeatedly [[polling (computer science)|polling]] the mail server, frequently checking it for new mail. The IMAP protocol includes the [[IMAP IDLE|IDLE]] command, which allows the server to tell the client when new messages arrive. The original [[BlackBerry]] was the first popular example of push-email in a wireless context.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}}\n\nAnother example is the [[PointCast (dotcom)|PointCast Network]], which was widely covered in the 1990s. It delivered news and stock market data as a screensaver. Both [[Netscape]] and [[Microsoft]] integrated push technology through the [[Channel Definition Format]] (CDF) into their software at the height of the [[browser wars]], but it was never very popular. CDF faded away and was removed from the browsers of the time, replaced in the 2000s with [[RSS]] (a pull system.)\n\nOther uses of push-enabled [[web application]]s include software updates distribution (\"push updates\"), market data distribution (stock tickers), online chat/messaging systems ([[webchat]]), auctions, online betting and gaming, sport results, monitoring consoles, and [[sensor network]] monitoring.\n\n== Examples ==\n===Webpush===\n\nThe Webpush proposal of the [[Internet Engineering Task Force]] is a simple protocol using [[HTTP/2|HTTP version 2]] to deliver realtime events, such as incoming calls or messages, which can be delivered (or \u201cpushed\u201d) in a timely fashion. The protocol consolidates all [[Real-time computing|real-time]] events into a single session which ensures more efficient use of network and radio resources.  A single service consolidates all events, distributing those events to applications as they arrive.  This requires just one session, avoiding duplicated overhead costs.<ref>{{Cite web |title= Generic Event Delivery Using HTTP Push |author= M. Thomson, E. Damaggio and B. Raymor |date= October 22, 2016 |work= Internet Draft |publisher= Internet Engineering Task Force |url= https://tools.ietf.org/html/draft-ietf-webpush-protocol-12 |accessdate= October 28, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nWeb Notifications are part of W3C standard and defines an [[API]] for end-user notifications. A notification allows alerting the user outside the context of a web page of an occurrence, such as the delivery of email.<ref>{{Cite web |title= Web Notifications |url= https://www.w3.org/TR/notifications/}}</ref> As part of this standard Push API defined by W3C, is now being implemented by Chrome, Firefox, Edge, and Safari.<ref>{{Cite web |title= Web Push API |url= https://www.w3.org/TR/push-api/}}</ref>\n\n=== HTTP server push ===\nHTTP server push (also known as HTTP streaming) is a mechanism for sending unsolicited (asynchronous) data from a [[web server]] to a [[web browser]]. HTTP server push can be achieved through any of several mechanisms.\n\nAs a part of HTML5 the [[WebSocket]] API allows a web server and client to communicate over a [[Duplex (telecommunications)|full-duplex]] TCP connection.\n\nGenerally the web server does not terminate a connection after response data has been served to a client. The web server leaves the connection open so that if an event occurs (for example, a change in internal data which needs to be reported to one or multiple clients), it can be sent out immediately; otherwise, the event would have to be queued until the client's next request is received. Most web servers offer this functionality via [[Common Gateway Interface|CGI]] (e.g., Non-Parsed Headers scripts on [[Apache HTTP Server]]). The underlying mechanism for this approach is [[chunked transfer encoding]].\n\nAnother mechanism is related to a special [[MIME]] type called <code>[[MIME#Mixed-Replace|multipart/x-mixed-replace]]</code>, which was introduced by [[Netscape]] in 1995. Web browsers interpret this as a document that changes whenever the server pushes a new version to the client.<ref>[http://www.oreilly.com/openbook/cgi/ch06_06.html CGI Programming on the World Wide Web] O'Reilly book explaining how to use Netscape server-push</ref> It is still supported by [[Mozilla Firefox|Firefox]], [[Opera (web browser)|Opera]], and [[Safari (web browser)|Safari]] today, but it is ignored by [[Internet Explorer]]<ref>[http://victor.transformadora.com/Oreilly/wdesign/xhtml/ch13_03.htm Server-Push Documents (HTML & XHTML: The Definitive Guide)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080417004248/http://victor.transformadora.com/Oreilly/wdesign/xhtml/ch13_03.htm |date=2008-04-17 }} O'Reilly book explaining server-push</ref> and is only partially supported by [[Google Chrome]].<ref>[https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=249132 Remove support for multipart/x-mixed-replace main resources]</ref> It can be applied to [[HTML]] documents, and also for streaming images in [[webcam]] applications.\n\nThe [[WHATWG]] Web Applications 1.0 proposal<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whatwg.org/specs/web-apps/current-work/#scs-server-sent|title=Web Applications 1.0 specification}}</ref> includes a mechanism to push content to the client. On September 1, 2006, the Opera web browser implemented this new experimental system in a feature called \"[[Server-sent events|Server-Sent Events]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://my.opera.com/WebApplications/blog/show.dml/438711|accessdate=2007-03-23|date=2006-09-01|title=Event Streaming to Web Browsers}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://operawatch.com/news/2006/09/opera-takes-the-lead-with-ajax-support-among-browsers-more-efficient-streaming.html|accessdate=2007-03-23|date=2006-09-01|title=Opera takes the lead with AJAX support among browsers: More efficient streaming|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070318013327/http://operawatch.com/news/2006/09/opera-takes-the-lead-with-ajax-support-among-browsers-more-efficient-streaming.html|archivedate=2007-03-18}}</ref> It is now being standardized as part of [[HTML5]].<ref>[https://www.w3.org/TR/eventsource/ Server-Sent Events]</ref>\n\n=== Pushlet ===\nIn this technique, the server takes advantage of [[HTTP persistent connection|persistent HTTP connections]], leaving the response perpetually \"open\" (i.e., the server never terminates the response), effectively fooling the browser to remain in \"loading\" mode after the initial page load could be considered complete. The server then periodically sends snippets of JavaScript to update the content of the page, thereby achieving push capability. By using this technique, the client doesn't need [[Java applet]]s or other plug-ins in order to keep an open connection to the server; the client is automatically notified about new events, pushed by the server.<ref>[http://www.pushlets.com/doc/whitepaper-toc.html Pushlets introduction]</ref><ref>[http://www.javaworld.com/jw-03-2000/jw-03-pushlet.html JavaWorld article about pushlets]\n</ref> One serious drawback to this method, however, is the lack of control the server has over the browser timing out; a page refresh is always necessary if a timeout occurs on the browser end.\n\n{{[[]]}}=== Long polling ===\nLong polling is itself not a true push; long polling is a variation of the traditional [[polling (computer science)|polling]] technique, but it allows emulating a push mechanism under circumstances where a real push is not possible, such as sites with security policies that require rejection of incoming HTTP/S Requests.\n\nWith long polling, the client requests information from the server exactly as in normal polling, but with the expectation the server may not respond immediately. If the server has no new information for the client when the poll is received, instead of sending an empty response, the server holds the request open and waits for response information to become available. Once it does have new information, the server immediately sends an HTTP/S response to the client, completing the open HTTP/S Request.  Upon receipt of the server response, the client often immediately issues another server request.  In this way the usual response latency (the time between when the information first becomes available and the next client request) otherwise associated with polling clients is eliminated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6202#section-2.1|accessdate=2016-05-14|title=RFC6202 - Known Issues and Best Practices for the Use of Long Polling and Streaming in Bidirectional HTTP}}</ref>\n\nFor example, [[BOSH (protocol)|BOSH]] is a popular, long-lived HTTP technique used as a long-polling alternative to a continuous TCP connection when such a connection is difficult or impossible to employ directly (e.g., in a web browser);<ref>{{cite web|url=http://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0124.html#intro|accessdate=2012-06-26|title=XEP-0124: Bidirectional-streams Over Synchronous HTTP (BOSH)}}</ref> it is also an underlying technology in the [[Extensible Messaging and Presence Protocol|XMPP]], which Apple uses for its iCloud push support.\n\n=== Flash XMLSocket relays ===\nThis technique, used by [[Cbox]] and other [[online chat|chat]] applications, makes use of the [[XMLSocket]] object in a single-pixel [[Adobe Flash]] movie. Under the control of [[JavaScript]], the client establishes a [[TCP connection]] to a [[unidirectional network|unidirectional]] relay on the server. The relay server does not read anything from this [[network socket|socket]]; instead it immediately sends the client a [[unique identifier]]. Next, the client makes an [[HTTP request]] to the web server, including with it this identifier. The web application can then push messages addressed to the client to a local interface of the relay server, which relays them over the Flash socket. The advantage of this approach is that it appreciates the natural read-write asymmetry that is typical of many web applications, including chat, and as a consequence it offers high efficiency. Since it does not accept data on outgoing sockets, the relay server does not need to poll outgoing TCP connections ''at all'', making it possible to hold open tens of thousands of concurrent connections. In this model, the limit to scale is the TCP stack of the underlying server operating system.\n\n=== Reliable Group Data Delivery (RGDD) ===\nIn services such as Cloud Computing, to increase reliability and availability of data, it is usually pushed (replicated) to several machines. For example, the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS) makes 2 extra copies of any object stored. RGDD focuses on efficiently casting an object from one location to many while saving bandwidth by sending minimal number of copies (only one in the best case) of the object over any link across the network. For example, Datacast <ref>{{Cite journal |title= Datacast: A Scalable and Efficient Reliable Group Data Delivery Service For Data Centers |journal= Microsoft Research|author= C. Guo|display-authors=etal|date= November 1, 2012 |publisher= ACM |url= https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/research/publication/datacast-a-scalable-and-efficient-reliable-group-data-delivery-service-for-data-centers-2/ |accessdate= Jun 6, 2017 }}</ref> is a scheme for delivery to many nodes inside datacenters that relies on regular and structured topologies and DCCast <ref>{{Cite web |title= DCCast: Efficient Point to Multipoint Transfers Across Datacenters |author= M. Noormohammadpour|display-authors=etal|date= July 10, 2017 |publisher= USENIX |url= https://www.researchgate.net/publication/316921061 |accessdate= Jun 6, 2017 }}</ref> is a similar approach for delivery across datacenters.\n\n===Push notification===\n\nA push notification is a message that is \"pushed\" from backend server or application to user interface, e.g. (but not limited to) mobile applications and desktop applications. Push notifications were first introduced by [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2008/06/09/iphone-push-notification-service-for-devs-announced/|title=iPhone push notification service for devs announced|website=Engadget|access-date=2016-10-18}}</ref>\nIn 2010 [[Google]] released its own service, Google Cloud to Device Messaging. (It has since been replaced by [[Google Cloud Messaging]] and then [[Firebase Cloud Messaging]].)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infoq.com/news/2012/08/GoogleCMReplacesC2Dm|title=Google Cloud Messaging for Android (GCM) Unveiled, to Replace C2DM Framework|website=InfoQ|access-date=2016-10-18}}</ref>\nNovember 2015, [[Microsoft]] announced that the [[Windows Notification Service]] would be expanded to make use of the Universal Windows Platform architecture, allowing for push data to be sent to Windows 10, Windows 10 Mobile, Xbox, as well as other supported platforms using universal API calls and POST requests.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/uwp/controls-and-patterns/tiles-and-notifications-windows-push-notification-services--wns--overview|title=Windows Push Notification Services (WNS) overview|last=mijacobs|website=docs.microsoft.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-10-20}}</ref>\n\nPush notifications are mainly divided into 2 approaches, local notifications and remote notifications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://developer.apple.com/library/archive/documentation/NetworkingInternet/Conceptual/RemoteNotificationsPG/|title=Local and Remote Notifications in Depth|last=|first=|date=|website=developer.apple.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2016-10-18}}</ref> For local notifications, the application schedules the notification with the local device's OS, or, alternatively, sets as a timer in the application itself if it is able to continuously run in the background. When the event's scheduled time is reached, or the event's programmed condition is met, the message is displayed in the application's user interface.\n\nRemote notifications are handled by a remote server. Under this scenario, the client application needs to be registered on the server with a unique key (e.g., a [[UUID]]). The server then fires the message against the unique key to deliver the message to the client application via an agreed client/server protocol such as [[HTTP]] or [[XMPP]] and the client displays the message received. When the push notification arrives, it can transmit short notifications and messages, set badges on application icons, blink or continuously light up the [[notification LED]], or play alert sounds to attract user's attention.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jatapp.com/blog/android-ios-push-notifications/|title=Android and iOS Push Notifications \u2013 Blog \u2013 JatApp|website=jatapp.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-20}}</ref> Push notifications are usually used by applications to bring information to users' attention. The content of the messages can be classified in the following example categories:\n* Chat messages, e.g.: messages from [[Facebook]] messenger sent by other users.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/help/103859036372845?helpref=faq_content|title=How do I adjust my mobile push notifications from Facebook? {{!}} Facebook Help Center {{!}} Facebook|website=www.facebook.com|access-date=2016-10-18}}</ref>\n* Vendor special offers, e.g.: A vendor may want to advertise their social offers to the customers.\n* Event reminder, e.g.: Some application may allow the customer to create reminder or alert for a specific time.\n* Subscribed topics changes, e.g.: Users may want to get updates regarding the weather in their location, or monitor a web page to track changes, for instance.\n\nReal-time push notifications may raise privacy issues since they can be used to bind virtual identities of social network pseudonyms to the real identities of the smartphone owners.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Loreti|first=Pierpaolo|last2=Bracciale|first2=Lorenzo|last3=Caponi|first3=Alberto|date=2018|title=Push Attack: Binding Virtual and Real Identities Using Mobile Push Notifications|journal= Future Internet|volume=10|issue=2|pages=13|doi=10.3390/fi10020013}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[BlazeDS]]\n* [[BOSH (protocol)|BOSH]]\n* [[Channel Definition Format]]\n* [[Client\u2013server model]]\n* [[Comet (programming)|Comet]]\n* [[File transfer]]\n* [[GraniteDS]]\n* [[Lightstreamer]]\n* [[Notification LED]]\n* [[Pull technology]]\n* [[Push Access Protocol]]\n* [[Push e-mail]]\n* [[HTTP/2]]\n* [[SQL Server Notification Services]]\n* [[Streaming media]]\n* [[WebSocket]]\n* [[WebSub]]\n\n== References ==\n {{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.w3.org/Architecture/9709_Workshop/ W3C Push Workshop]. A 1997 workshop that discussed push technology and some early examples thereof\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051201013553/http://ajaxpatterns.org/HTTP_Streaming HTTP Streaming with Ajax] A description of HTTP Streaming from the Ajax Patterns website\n* [http://www.w3.org/TR/websockets/ The WebSocket API] candidate recommendation\n* [http://www.w3.org/TR/eventsource/ HTML5 Server-Sent Events] draft specification\n\n{{Web syndication}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Push Technology}}\n[[Category:Ajax (programming)]]\n[[Category:Internet terminology]]\n[[Category:Mobile technology]]\n[[Category:Push technology| ]]\n[[Category:Web development]]\n", "text_old": "{{tone|date=January 2019}}\n'''Push notifications'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pushmaze.com/what-is-push-notifications/|title=What is push notifications & How do push notifications work?|website=www.pushmaze.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-25|date=2018-09-22}}</ref> are small messages that can reach audiences anywhere and anytime. While pop-ups appear only when audiences are on the site they belong to, push messages are independent of sites. They are associated with web browsers and apps. \n\n'''Push technology''', or '''server push''', is a style of [[Internet]]-based communication where the request for a given transaction is initiated by the publisher or central [[server (computing)|server]]. It is contrasted with [[pull technology|pull]]/get, where the request for the transmission of information is initiated by the receiver or [[client (computing)|client]].\n\nPush services are often based on information preferences expressed in advance. This is called a [[publish/subscribe]] model. A client \"subscribes\" to various information \"channels\" provided by a server; whenever new content is available on one of those channels, the server pushes that information out to the client.\n\nPush is sometimes emulated with a [[polling (computer science)|polling]] technique, particularly under circumstances where a real push is not possible, such as sites with security policies that require rejection of incoming HTTP/S requests.\n\n== General use ==\n[[Synchronous conferencing]] and [[instant messaging]] are typical examples of push services. Chat messages and sometimes [[Computer file|files]] are pushed to the user as soon as they are received by the messaging service. Both decentralised [[peer-to-peer]] programs (such as [[WASTE]]) and centralised programs (such as [[Internet Relay Chat|IRC]] or [[Extensible Messaging and Presence Protocol|XMPP]]) allow pushing files, which means the sender initiates the data transfer rather than the recipient.\n\n[[Email]] may also be a push system: [[SMTP]] is a push protocol (see [[Push e-mail]]). However, the last step\u2014from mail server to desktop computer\u2014typically uses a pull protocol like [[POP3]] or [[IMAP]]. Modern e-mail clients make this step seem instantaneous by repeatedly [[polling (computer science)|polling]] the mail server, frequently checking it for new mail. The IMAP protocol includes the [[IMAP IDLE|IDLE]] command, which allows the server to tell the client when new messages arrive. The original [[BlackBerry]] was the first popular example of push-email in a wireless context.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}}\n\nAnother example is the [[PointCast (dotcom)|PointCast Network]], which was widely covered in the 1990s. It delivered news and stock market data as a screensaver. Both [[Netscape]] and [[Microsoft]] integrated push technology through the [[Channel Definition Format]] (CDF) into their software at the height of the [[browser wars]], but it was never very popular. CDF faded away and was removed from the browsers of the time, replaced in the 2000s with [[RSS]] (a pull system.)\n\nOther uses of push-enabled [[web application]]s include software updates distribution (\"push updates\"), market data distribution (stock tickers), online chat/messaging systems ([[webchat]]), auctions, online betting and gaming, sport results, monitoring consoles, and [[sensor network]] monitoring.\n\n== Examples ==\n===Webpush===\n\nThe Webpush proposal of the [[Internet Engineering Task Force]] is a simple protocol using [[HTTP/2|HTTP version 2]] to deliver realtime events, such as incoming calls or messages, which can be delivered (or \u201cpushed\u201d) in a timely fashion. The protocol consolidates all [[Real-time computing|real-time]] events into a single session which ensures more efficient use of network and radio resources.  A single service consolidates all events, distributing those events to applications as they arrive.  This requires just one session, avoiding duplicated overhead costs.<ref>{{Cite web |title= Generic Event Delivery Using HTTP Push |author= M. Thomson, E. Damaggio and B. Raymor |date= October 22, 2016 |work= Internet Draft |publisher= Internet Engineering Task Force |url= https://tools.ietf.org/html/draft-ietf-webpush-protocol-12 |accessdate= October 28, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nWeb Notifications are part of W3C standard and defines an [[API]] for end-user notifications. A notification allows alerting the user outside the context of a web page of an occurrence, such as the delivery of email.<ref>{{Cite web |title= Web Notifications |url= https://www.w3.org/TR/notifications/}}</ref> As part of this standard Push API defined by W3C, is now being implemented by Chrome, Firefox, Edge, and Safari.<ref>{{Cite web |title= Web Push API |url= https://www.w3.org/TR/push-api/}}</ref>\n\n=== HTTP server push ===\nHTTP server push (also known as HTTP streaming) is a mechanism for sending unsolicited (asynchronous) data from a [[web server]] to a [[web browser]]. HTTP server push can be achieved through any of several mechanisms.\n\nAs a part of HTML5 the [[WebSocket]] API allows a web server and client to communicate over a [[Duplex (telecommunications)|full-duplex]] TCP connection.\n\nGenerally the web server does not terminate a connection after response data has been served to a client. The web server leaves the connection open so that if an event occurs (for example, a change in internal data which needs to be reported to one or multiple clients), it can be sent out immediately; otherwise, the event would have to be queued until the client's next request is received. Most web servers offer this functionality via [[Common Gateway Interface|CGI]] (e.g., Non-Parsed Headers scripts on [[Apache HTTP Server]]). The underlying mechanism for this approach is [[chunked transfer encoding]].\n\nAnother mechanism is related to a special [[MIME]] type called <code>[[MIME#Mixed-Replace|multipart/x-mixed-replace]]</code>, which was introduced by [[Netscape]] in 1995. Web browsers interpret this as a document that changes whenever the server pushes a new version to the client.<ref>[http://www.oreilly.com/openbook/cgi/ch06_06.html CGI Programming on the World Wide Web] O'Reilly book explaining how to use Netscape server-push</ref> It is still supported by [[Mozilla Firefox|Firefox]], [[Opera (web browser)|Opera]], and [[Safari (web browser)|Safari]] today, but it is ignored by [[Internet Explorer]]<ref>[http://victor.transformadora.com/Oreilly/wdesign/xhtml/ch13_03.htm Server-Push Documents (HTML & XHTML: The Definitive Guide)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080417004248/http://victor.transformadora.com/Oreilly/wdesign/xhtml/ch13_03.htm |date=2008-04-17 }} O'Reilly book explaining server-push</ref> and is only partially supported by [[Google Chrome]].<ref>[https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=249132 Remove support for multipart/x-mixed-replace main resources]</ref> It can be applied to [[HTML]] documents, and also for streaming images in [[webcam]] applications.\n\nThe [[WHATWG]] Web Applications 1.0 proposal<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whatwg.org/specs/web-apps/current-work/#scs-server-sent|title=Web Applications 1.0 specification}}</ref> includes a mechanism to push content to the client. On September 1, 2006, the Opera web browser implemented this new experimental system in a feature called \"[[Server-sent events|Server-Sent Events]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://my.opera.com/WebApplications/blog/show.dml/438711|accessdate=2007-03-23|date=2006-09-01|title=Event Streaming to Web Browsers}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://operawatch.com/news/2006/09/opera-takes-the-lead-with-ajax-support-among-browsers-more-efficient-streaming.html|accessdate=2007-03-23|date=2006-09-01|title=Opera takes the lead with AJAX support among browsers: More efficient streaming|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070318013327/http://operawatch.com/news/2006/09/opera-takes-the-lead-with-ajax-support-among-browsers-more-efficient-streaming.html|archivedate=2007-03-18}}</ref> It is now being standardized as part of [[HTML5]].<ref>[https://www.w3.org/TR/eventsource/ Server-Sent Events]</ref>\n\n=== Pushlet ===\nIn this technique, the server takes advantage of [[HTTP persistent connection|persistent HTTP connections]], leaving the response perpetually \"open\" (i.e., the server never terminates the response), effectively fooling the browser to remain in \"loading\" mode after the initial page load could be considered complete. The server then periodically sends snippets of JavaScript to update the content of the page, thereby achieving push capability. By using this technique, the client doesn't need [[Java applet]]s or other plug-ins in order to keep an open connection to the server; the client is automatically notified about new events, pushed by the server.<ref>[http://www.pushlets.com/doc/whitepaper-toc.html Pushlets introduction]</ref><ref>[http://www.javaworld.com/jw-03-2000/jw-03-pushlet.html JavaWorld article about pushlets]\n</ref> One serious drawback to this method, however, is the lack of control the server has over the browser timing out; a page refresh is always necessary if a timeout occurs on the browser end.\n\n=== Long polling ===\nLong polling is itself not a true push; long polling is a variation of the traditional [[polling (computer science)|polling]] technique, but it allows emulating a push mechanism under circumstances where a real push is not possible, such as sites with security policies that require rejection of incoming HTTP/S Requests.\n\nWith long polling, the client requests information from the server exactly as in normal polling, but with the expectation the server may not respond immediately. If the server has no new information for the client when the poll is received, instead of sending an empty response, the server holds the request open and waits for response information to become available. Once it does have new information, the server immediately sends an HTTP/S response to the client, completing the open HTTP/S Request.  Upon receipt of the server response, the client often immediately issues another server request.  In this way the usual response latency (the time between when the information first becomes available and the next client request) otherwise associated with polling clients is eliminated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6202#section-2.1|accessdate=2016-05-14|title=RFC6202 - Known Issues and Best Practices for the Use of Long Polling and Streaming in Bidirectional HTTP}}</ref>\n\nFor example, [[BOSH (protocol)|BOSH]] is a popular, long-lived HTTP technique used as a long-polling alternative to a continuous TCP connection when such a connection is difficult or impossible to employ directly (e.g., in a web browser);<ref>{{cite web|url=http://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0124.html#intro|accessdate=2012-06-26|title=XEP-0124: Bidirectional-streams Over Synchronous HTTP (BOSH)}}</ref> it is also an underlying technology in the [[Extensible Messaging and Presence Protocol|XMPP]], which Apple uses for its iCloud push support.\n\n=== Flash XMLSocket relays ===\nThis technique, used by [[Cbox]] and other [[online chat|chat]] applications, makes use of the [[XMLSocket]] object in a single-pixel [[Adobe Flash]] movie. Under the control of [[JavaScript]], the client establishes a [[TCP connection]] to a [[unidirectional network|unidirectional]] relay on the server. The relay server does not read anything from this [[network socket|socket]]; instead it immediately sends the client a [[unique identifier]]. Next, the client makes an [[HTTP request]] to the web server, including with it this identifier. The web application can then push messages addressed to the client to a local interface of the relay server, which relays them over the Flash socket. The advantage of this approach is that it appreciates the natural read-write asymmetry that is typical of many web applications, including chat, and as a consequence it offers high efficiency. Since it does not accept data on outgoing sockets, the relay server does not need to poll outgoing TCP connections ''at all'', making it possible to hold open tens of thousands of concurrent connections. In this model, the limit to scale is the TCP stack of the underlying server operating system.\n\n=== Reliable Group Data Delivery (RGDD) ===\nIn services such as Cloud Computing, to increase reliability and availability of data, it is usually pushed (replicated) to several machines. For example, the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS) makes 2 extra copies of any object stored. RGDD focuses on efficiently casting an object from one location to many while saving bandwidth by sending minimal number of copies (only one in the best case) of the object over any link across the network. For example, Datacast <ref>{{Cite journal |title= Datacast: A Scalable and Efficient Reliable Group Data Delivery Service For Data Centers |journal= Microsoft Research|author= C. Guo|display-authors=etal|date= November 1, 2012 |publisher= ACM |url= https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/research/publication/datacast-a-scalable-and-efficient-reliable-group-data-delivery-service-for-data-centers-2/ |accessdate= Jun 6, 2017 }}</ref> is a scheme for delivery to many nodes inside datacenters that relies on regular and structured topologies and DCCast <ref>{{Cite web |title= DCCast: Efficient Point to Multipoint Transfers Across Datacenters |author= M. Noormohammadpour|display-authors=etal|date= July 10, 2017 |publisher= USENIX |url= https://www.researchgate.net/publication/316921061 |accessdate= Jun 6, 2017 }}</ref> is a similar approach for delivery across datacenters.\n\n===Push notification===\n\nA push notification is a message that is \"pushed\" from backend server or application to user interface, e.g. (but not limited to) mobile applications and desktop applications. Push notifications were first introduced by [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2008/06/09/iphone-push-notification-service-for-devs-announced/|title=iPhone push notification service for devs announced|website=Engadget|access-date=2016-10-18}}</ref>\nIn 2010 [[Google]] released its own service, Google Cloud to Device Messaging. (It has since been replaced by [[Google Cloud Messaging]] and then [[Firebase Cloud Messaging]].)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infoq.com/news/2012/08/GoogleCMReplacesC2Dm|title=Google Cloud Messaging for Android (GCM) Unveiled, to Replace C2DM Framework|website=InfoQ|access-date=2016-10-18}}</ref>\nNovember 2015, [[Microsoft]] announced that the [[Windows Notification Service]] would be expanded to make use of the Universal Windows Platform architecture, allowing for push data to be sent to Windows 10, Windows 10 Mobile, Xbox, as well as other supported platforms using universal API calls and POST requests.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/uwp/controls-and-patterns/tiles-and-notifications-windows-push-notification-services--wns--overview|title=Windows Push Notification Services (WNS) overview|last=mijacobs|website=docs.microsoft.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-10-20}}</ref>\n\nPush notifications are mainly divided into 2 approaches, local notifications and remote notifications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://developer.apple.com/library/archive/documentation/NetworkingInternet/Conceptual/RemoteNotificationsPG/|title=Local and Remote Notifications in Depth|last=|first=|date=|website=developer.apple.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2016-10-18}}</ref> For local notifications, the application schedules the notification with the local device's OS, or, alternatively, sets as a timer in the application itself if it is able to continuously run in the background. When the event's scheduled time is reached, or the event's programmed condition is met, the message is displayed in the application's user interface.\n\nRemote notifications are handled by a remote server. Under this scenario, the client application needs to be registered on the server with a unique key (e.g., a [[UUID]]). The server then fires the message against the unique key to deliver the message to the client application via an agreed client/server protocol such as [[HTTP]] or [[XMPP]] and the client displays the message received. When the push notification arrives, it can transmit short notifications and messages, set badges on application icons, blink or continuously light up the [[notification LED]], or play alert sounds to attract user's attention.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jatapp.com/blog/android-ios-push-notifications/|title=Android and iOS Push Notifications \u2013 Blog \u2013 JatApp|website=jatapp.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-20}}</ref> Push notifications are usually used by applications to bring information to users' attention. The content of the messages can be classified in the following example categories:\n* Chat messages, e.g.: messages from [[Facebook]] messenger sent by other users.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/help/103859036372845?helpref=faq_content|title=How do I adjust my mobile push notifications from Facebook? {{!}} Facebook Help Center {{!}} Facebook|website=www.facebook.com|access-date=2016-10-18}}</ref>\n* Vendor special offers, e.g.: A vendor may want to advertise their social offers to the customers.\n* Event reminder, e.g.: Some application may allow the customer to create reminder or alert for a specific time.\n* Subscribed topics changes, e.g.: Users may want to get updates regarding the weather in their location, or monitor a web page to track changes, for instance.\n\nReal-time push notifications may raise privacy issues since they can be used to bind virtual identities of social network pseudonyms to the real identities of the smartphone owners.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Loreti|first=Pierpaolo|last2=Bracciale|first2=Lorenzo|last3=Caponi|first3=Alberto|date=2018|title=Push Attack: Binding Virtual and Real Identities Using Mobile Push Notifications|journal= Future Internet|volume=10|issue=2|pages=13|doi=10.3390/fi10020013}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[BlazeDS]]\n* [[BOSH (protocol)|BOSH]]\n* [[Channel Definition Format]]\n* [[Client\u2013server model]]\n* [[Comet (programming)|Comet]]\n* [[File transfer]]\n* [[GraniteDS]]\n* [[Lightstreamer]]\n* [[Notification LED]]\n* [[Pull technology]]\n* [[Push Access Protocol]]\n* [[Push e-mail]]\n* [[HTTP/2]]\n* [[SQL Server Notification Services]]\n* [[Streaming media]]\n* [[WebSocket]]\n* [[WebSub]]\n\n== References ==\n {{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.w3.org/Architecture/9709_Workshop/ W3C Push Workshop]. A 1997 workshop that discussed push technology and some early examples thereof\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051201013553/http://ajaxpatterns.org/HTTP_Streaming HTTP Streaming with Ajax] A description of HTTP Streaming from the Ajax Patterns website\n* [http://www.w3.org/TR/websockets/ The WebSocket API] candidate recommendation\n* [http://www.w3.org/TR/eventsource/ HTML5 Server-Sent Events] draft specification\n\n{{Web syndication}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Push Technology}}\n[[Category:Ajax (programming)]]\n[[Category:Internet terminology]]\n[[Category:Mobile technology]]\n[[Category:Push technology| ]]\n[[Category:Web development]]\n", "name_user": "96.9.87.69", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eLong polling:Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Push_technology"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Vermont", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in Vermont, United States}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Vermont\n| map1            = \n| places          = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Vermont]]\n| first_case      = [[Bennington, Vermont|Bennington]]<ref name=\"vtdigger20200307\" />\n| arrival_date    = March 7, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=8|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 338\n| deaths          = 17\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://www.healthvermont.gov/covid}}\n}}\nThe 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Vermont]] is part of an ongoing worldwide [[Viral disease|viral]] [[pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] ({{nowrap|COVID-19}}), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus&nbsp;2]] ({{nowrap|SARS-CoV-2}}).\n{{2019\u201320_coronavirus_pandemic_data/United_States/Vermont_medical_cases_chart}}\n\n==Timeline==\nThe [[Vermont Department of Health|Vermont Department of Heath]] announced the state's first case of COVID-19 on Saturday, March 7, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lamdin |first1=Courtney |title=Vermont Health Department Reports the State's First Coronavirus Case |url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/OffMessage/archives/2020/03/07/vermont-health-department-reports-the-states-first-coronavirus-case|url-status=live |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=SevenDays VT |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> The patient was subsequently identified as being in a [[Southwestern Vermont Medical Center|hospital]] in Bennington, Vermont.<ref name=\"vtdigger20200307\">{{cite news |last1=Walters |first1=John |title=Bennington patient Vermont's first 'presumptive positive' coronavirus case |url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/07/vermont-has-first-presumptive-case-of-coronavirus/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=VTDigger |date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, the first two deaths from COVID-19 were announced, one a male in [[White River Junction, Vermont|White River Junction]] and the other a female in [[Burlington, Vermont|Burlington]]. Both were over 80 years old.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Landen|first1=Xander|url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/19/two-die-from-coronavirus-infections-in-vermont/|title=Two die from coronavirus infections in Vermont|date=19 March 2020|work=VTDigger|accessdate=20 March 2020|url-status=live|last2=Jickling|first2=Katie}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, it was announced that three more people had died at a Burlington nursing home, bringing the statewide total to five deaths from COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lamdin |first1=Courtney |title=Three More Dead of Coronavirus at Burlington Nursing Home |url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/OffMessage/archives/2020/03/23/four-people-dead-of-coronavirus-at-burlington-nursing-home |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Seven Days VT |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, the Vermont Department of Health announced two more deaths, including one more at a Burlington nursing home where four other residents have died from COVID-19. The state also announced they have tested 1,535 samples since March 7, and have increased the testing capacity across the state.<ref name=\"sevendaysvt-20200324\">{{cite news |last1=Kamdin |first1=Courtney |title=Vermont Reports Two More Deaths as Coronavirus Cases Climb |url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/OffMessage/archives/2020/03/24/vermont-reports-two-more-deaths-as-coronavirus-cases-climb |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=SevenDaysVT |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, the eighth death in Vermont was announced, again of a resident at the same Burlington nursing home where five other residents have died.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Flanders |first1=Colin |title=Vermont Seeing 'Exponential Growth' of Coronavirus |url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/OffMessage/archives/2020/03/25/vermont-seeing-exponential-growth-of-coronavirus |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Seven Days VT |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, the Vermont Department of Health reported 37 new confirmed cases, the most reported in a single day, with the number of deaths rising to 13.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Flanders |first1=Colin |title=Vermont Announces 37 More Coronavirus Cases, One New Death |url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/OffMessage/archives/2020/03/31/vermont-announces-37-more-coronavirus-cases-one-new-death |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=Seven Days VT |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Economic and social effects==\n\n===Schools closed===\n\nAll schools were ordered to be closed for in-person classes as of Wednesday, March 18, until at least April 6, 2020.<ref name=\"vtdigger20200315\" /> On March 26, this closure was extended through the rest of the academic year.<ref name=\"vt-state-directive-5\" />\n\nOn March 23, the [[University of Vermont]] declared that all students must leave the UVM campus by March 30, except for those approved for emergency housing. Courses will be taught online for the remainder of the semester. UVM officials also indicated they will make a decision about canceling UVM's commencement ceremony by the end of March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Galloway |first1=Anne |title=UVM sends students home |url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/23/uvm-sends-students-home/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=VTDigger |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Restaurants and bars closed===\n\nBars and restaurants were ordered to close by 2:00pm on Tuesday, March 17, and to remain closed until April 6. Restaurants were allowed to continue providing takeout and delivery service.<ref name=\"vtdigger20200316-bars\">{{cite news |last1=Wallace Allen |first1=Anne |title=Bars and restaurants in Vermont will be ordered closed at 2 p.m. Tuesday: Scott admin |url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/16/bars-and-restaurants-in-vermont-will-be-ordered-closed-at-2-p-m-tuesday-scott-admin/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=VTDigger |date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> All gyms, spas, hair salons and tattoo parlors were ordered closed as of 8:00pm on March 23, 2020.<ref name=\"vtdigger20200321\" />\n\n=== Impact on media ===\n\nOn March 17, the publisher of three newspapers in southern Vermont, [[Brattleboro Reformer]], [[Bennington Banner]] and [[Manchester Journal]] indicated that all full-time staff members would be furloughed for one of the next five weeks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Heintz |first1=Paul |title=Media Note: Vermont News Outlets Ramp Up as Outbreak Threatens Business |url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/OffMessage/archives/2020/03/19/media-note-vermont-news-outlets-ramp-up-as-outbreak-threatens-business |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=Seven Days VT |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, the [[Barre Montpelier Times Argus|''Barre Montpelier Times Argu''s]] and ''[[Rutland Herald]]'' newspapers announced that due to the financial impact of the pandemic they would be reducing their print publishing to three days a week and temporarily laying off 20 staffpeople.<ref name=\"times-argus-20200322\">{{cite news |last1=Pappas |first1=Steve |title=City Room: COVID-19's effects on us |url=https://www.timesargus.com/news/covid19/city-room-covid--s-effects-on-us/article_35074189-82f9-5fbd-b695-ef5cc3f5751a.html|url-status=live |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Times Argus |publisher=Brunswick Publishing LLC |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, ''[[Seven Days (newspaper)|Seven Days]]'' indicated they would lay off seven employees.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Heintz |first1=Paul |title=Media Note: Seven Days Lays Off Seven Employees |url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/OffMessage/archives/2020/03/23/media-note-seven-days-lays-off-seven-employees |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=Seven Days |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government response==\nOn March 10, the Vermont State Emergency Operations Center was activated.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://vem.vermont.gov/news/governor-phil-scott-orders-activation-state-emergency-operations-center|title=Governor Phil Scott Orders Activation of State Emergency Operations Center|date=2020-03-10|website=Vermont Emergency Management}}</ref> On March 13, a COVID-19 task force was set up<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://vem.vermont.gov/news/governor-phil-scott-details-development-covid-19-task-force|title=Governor Phil Scott Details Development of COVID-19 Task Force|website=Vermont Emergency Management|date=2020-03-02}}</ref> and  Governor [[Phil Scott (politician)|Phil Scott]] issued Executive Order 01-20 which declared a State of Emergency until it expires on April 15.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/OffMessage/archives/2020/03/13/governor-scott-declares-state-of-emergency-in-vermont|title=Scott Declares State of Emergency in Vermont|newspaper=Seven Days|date=2020-03-13|first=Colin|last=Flanders}}</ref> The Executive Order limits visitors to nursing homes, assisted living residences, residential care homes, and specific care facilities.  It also suspends traveling by state employees for non-essential government business, prohibits most mass gatherings including at schools and excluding transit, most offices, and grocery and commercial stores.  The [[Vermont National Guard|National Guard]] was also activated.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://governor.vermont.gov/content/declaration-state-emergency-response-covid-19-and-national-guard-call-out-executive-order-01|title=DECLARATION OF STATE OF EMERGENCY IN RESPONSE TO COVID-19 AND NATIONAL GUARD CALL-OUT (EXECUTIVE ORDER 01-20)]|website=Office of Governor Phil Scott}}</ref> Additionally, the [[Vermont General Assembly]] voted to adjourn until March 24 to prepare for the virus.<ref>[https://www.wcax.com/content/news/Vermont-statehouse-to-adjourn--568770941.html Vermont Statehouse to temporarily shut down next week] [[WCAX]]</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Governor Phil Scott ordered all schools in Vermont to be closed and all school activities to be cancelled no later than Wednesday, March 18, and lasting through at least April 6.<ref name=\"vtdigger20200315\">{{cite news|last1=Duffort|first1=Lola|url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/15/scott-orders-schools-to-close/|title=Scott orders schools to close|date=2020-03-15|work=VTDigger|accessdate=16 March 2020|url-status=live|publisher=|last2=Galloway|first2=Anne}}</ref><ref name=\"stateofvt-scott-school-closure\">{{cite web |title=Gov. Scott Orders Orderly Closure of Vermont preK-12 Schools This Week |url=https://governor.vermont.gov/press-release/gov-scott-orders-orderly-closure-vermont-prek-12-schools-week |website=Office of Governor Phil Scott |publisher=State of Vermont |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> On March 16, Governor Scott announced his emergency declaration would be amended to limit public gatherings to either 50 people or 50% occupancy.<ref name=\"vtdigger20200316-50\">{{cite news |last1=Katie Jickling |first1=Lola Duffort |title=Update: Vermont now up to 12 cases as Scott limits gatherings to 50 |url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/16/vermont-now-up-to-12-coronavirus-cases-scott-administration-says/ |accessdate=16 March 2020 |publisher=VT Digger |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> Also on March 16, Burlington Mayor [[Miro Weinberger]] declared a state of emergency for Burlington and ordered all bars and restaurants to close Tuesday starting at 6:00am and continuing for at least 24 hours. All nonessential city services will also be suspended from Wednesday, March 18, through at least April 6.<ref>{{cite news |title=Burlington restaurants, bars to close for 24 hours |url=https://www.wcax.com/content/news/Burlington-restaurants-bars-to-close-for-24-hours-568839021.html |accessdate=16 March 2020 |publisher=WCAX |date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Miro Weinberger Declares Emergency and Announces New City Actions in Response to COVID-19 |url=https://www.burlingtonvt.gov/Press/mayor-miro-weinberger-declares-emergency-and-announces-new-city-actions-in-response-to-covid |website=City of Burlington |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Governor Scott ordered the closure of all Vermont child care programs, except for those that serve people \"essential\" to responding to the pandemic.<ref name=\"bfp-20200318\">{{cite news |last1=McCullum |first1=April |title=Gov. Scott orders closure of child care programs not serving 'essential' workers |url=https://www.burlingtonfreepress.com/story/news/local/vermont/2020/03/17/vermont-gov-phil-scott-order-child-care-closures-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/5073017002/ |accessdate=18 March 2020 |publisher=Burlington Free Press |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> The closure starts on Wednesday, March 18, and lasts through April 6. The governor's order defines \"essential\" persons as healthcare providers, criminal justice personnel; public health employees; firefighters; Vermont National Guard personnel; other first responders and state employees; and staff and providers of necessary childcare services.<ref name=\"scott-20200317\">{{cite web |title=Governor Phil Scott Orders Implementation Of Child Care System For Personnel Essential To Covid-19 Response - Childcare Centers Closed; Urged to Provide Care for Children of Vermonters Responding to Crisis |url=https://governor.vermont.gov/press-release/governor-phil-scott-orders-implementation-child-care-system-personnel-essential-covid |website=Office of Governor Phil Scott |publisher=State of Vermont |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Governor Scott announced that he would be working with the VT state legislature to develop a loan program through the Vermont Economic Development Authority (VEDA) for businesses impacted economically by the pandemic.<ref name=\"vtdigger20200320\">{{cite news |last1=Landen |first1=Xander |title=Scott says he's not considering shelter in place order at this time |url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/20/scott-says-hes-not-considering-shelter-in-place-order-at-this-time/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |publisher=VTDigger |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> He also announced that Vermont businesses can apply for economic injury disaster loans through the [[Small Business Administration]] (SBA).<ref name=\"philscott20200320\">{{cite web |title=Governor Phil Scott Announces Economic Injury Disaster Loans Available to Small Businesses Affected by COVID-19 |url=https://governor.vermont.gov/press-release/governor-phil-scott-announces-economic-injury-disaster-loans-available-small |website=Office of Governor Phil Scott |publisher=State of Vermont |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> The Vermont Senate will reconvene on Tuesday, March 24, to act on measures to respond to COVID-19.<ref name=\"vtdigger20200320-senate\">{{cite news |last1=Xander Landen |first1=Kit Norten |title=Senate to return to the Statehouse next week to pass COVID-19 measures |url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/20/senate-to-return-to-the-statehouse-next-week-to-pass-covid-19-measures/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |publisher=VTDigger |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Vermont state officials also stated that the number of available beds statewide has increased to 500 and the number of available ventilators has increased to 240.<ref name=\"sevendaysvt-20200320\">{{cite news |last1=Flanders |first1=Colin |title=Bracing for Coronavirus Spread, Vermont Frees Up Hospital Beds |url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/OffMessage/archives/2020/03/20/bracing-for-coronavirus-spread-vermont-frees-up-hospital-beds |accessdate=20 March 2020 |publisher=SevenDays VT |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, Governor Scott ordered the closure of gyms and similar exercise facilities, hair salons, spas and tattoo parlors by 8 pm on March 23. He also extended his earlier executive order to restrict gatherings to no more than 10 people.<ref name=\"vtdigger20200321\">{{cite news |last1=Allen |first1=Anne Wallace |title=Scott orders gyms, salons closed; limits gatherings to no more than 10 |url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/21/scott-orders-gyms-salons-closed-limits-gatherings-to-no-more-than-10/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=VTDigger |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> On March 23, Governor Scott ordered the [[Vermont National Guard]] and the Vermont Emergency Operations Center to set up a medical \"surge site\" to respond to COVID-19 cases.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Galloway |first1=Anne |title=Three more die at Burlington Health and Rehab of COVID-19 |url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/23/three-more-die-at-burlington-health-and-rehab-of-covid-19/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=VTDigger |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Governor Scott also announced that the Vermont Department of Public Service released a [https://publicservice.vermont.gov/announcements/public-wifi-hotspots-vermont \"Public Wi-Fi Hot Spot Map\"] to enable people in Vermont to find places to access the Internet for free.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://governor.vermont.gov/press-release/governor-phil-scott-announces-wi-fi-hot-spot-map|title=Governor Phil Scott Announces Public Service Department Wi-Fi Hot Spot Map to Help Vermonters Access Internet During COVID-19|website=State of Vermont - Office of Governor Phil Scott|date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, Governor Scott issued a \"Stay Home, Stay Safe\" order directing all residents of Vermont to stay home \"leaving only for essential reasons, critical to health and safety.\" The order directs that all businesses and not-for-profit entities must suspend all in-person business operations, except for specific exemptions. The order will remain in effect until April 15, 2020, unless extended or shortened.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://governor.vermont.gov/press-release/governor-phil-scott-issues-%E2%80%9Cstay-home-stay-safe%E2%80%9D-order-directs-additional-closures|title=GOVERNOR PHIL SCOTT ISSUES A \"STAY HOME, STAY SAFE\" ORDER, DIRECTS ADDITIONAL CLOSURES|website=Office of Governor Phil Scott}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Meyn |first1=Colin |title=\"Stay home,\" Scott orders in response to COVID-19 outbreak in Vermont |url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/24/stay-home-scott-orders-in-response-to-covid-19-outbreak-in-vermont/ |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=VTDigger |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> On March 26, Governor Scott ordered all schools in Vermont to remain closed for in-person classes for the rest of the academic year. School districts have until April 13 to produce distance learning plans for the remainder of the school year.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reed |first1=Elodie |last2=Elder-Connors |first2=Liam |title=Gov. Closes Vermont Schools For Rest Of Academic Year |url=https://www.vpr.org/post/gov-closes-vermont-schools-rest-academic-year |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=Vermont Public Radio |date=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vt-state-directive-5\">{{cite web |title=Directive 5 - Continuity of Learning Planning (Pursuant to EO 01-20) |url=https://governor.vermont.gov/content/directive-5-continuity-learning-planning-pursuant-eo-01-20 |website=Office of Governor Phil Scott |publisher=State of Vermont |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, Governor Scott imposed quarantine restrictions on travelers arriving in Vermont.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vpr.org/post/governor-orders-14-day-quarantine-out-state-travelers|title=Governor Orders 14-Day Quarantine For Out-Of-State Travelers|last=Giles|first=Mark Davis, Abagael|website=www.vpr.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> On March 31, the Vermont Agency of Commerce and Community Development ordered large retailers \"to cease in-person sales of non-essential items in order to reduce the number of people coming into the stores.\" The agency also ordered stores to close showrooms and garden sections of home improvement centers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Asch |first1=Sarah |title=Vermont orders big retailers to cease in-person sales on non-essential items |url=https://vtdigger.org/liveblog/vermont-orders-big-retailers-to-cease-in-person-sales-on-non-essential-items/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=VTDigger |date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Also, Governor Phil Scott announced the launch of a new website - [https://www.vermont.gov/volunteer https://www.vermont.gov/volunteer] - where Vermonters can sign up to volunteer to help in the state's response to COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Asch |first1=Sarah |title=Governor calls on Vermonters to pitch in with COVID-19 response |url=https://vtdigger.org/liveblog/governor-calls-on-vermonters-to-pitch-in-with-covid-19-response/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=VTDigger |date=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Governor Scott Calls on Vermonters to Support COVID-19 Response |url=https://governor.vermont.gov/press-release/governor-scott-calls-vermonters-to-service |website=Office of Governor Phil Scott |publisher=State of Vermont |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, Governor Scott announced that the State, in anticipation of a surge in COVID-19 cases, was preparing two additional medical surge locations in partnership with the Vermont National Guard: a 400-bed location at the Champlain Valley Exposition in [[Essex Junction, Vermont|Essex Junction]], and a 150-bed location in [[Rutland County, Vermont|Rutland County]]. Additional rapid reaction medical surge trailers, each containing materials for 50 additional beds, had been prepositioned throughout the state to facilitate rapid deployment. Additional assets, including two state portable hospitals, were also being prepared. These measures are a continuation in the State's plan to prevent hospitals from exceeding their capacities in the event of a surge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://governor.vermont.gov/press-release/governor-phil-scott-announces-additional-medical-surge-locations|title=Governor Phil Scott Announces Additional Medical Surge Locations|last=|first=|date=|website=Office of Governor Phil Scott|publisher=State of Vermont|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Vermont<ref name=\"vt-doh-covid\">{{cite web |title=Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) |url=https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/infectious-disease/2019-novel-coronavirus |website=Department of Health |publisher=State of Vermont |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\nUpdated April 2, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Addison\n|26\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Bennington\n|17\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Caledonia\n|4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Chittenden\n|177\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Essex\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Franklin\n|16\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Grand Isle\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Lamoille\n|14\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Orange\n|4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Orleans\n|7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Rutland\n|12\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Washington\n|18\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Windham\n|18\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Windsor\n|20\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |''N/A''{{ref label|unassigned|a|a}}\n|5\n|-\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |338\n|}\n{| style=\"margin: 1em auto;\"\n|-\n|{{note label|unassigned|a|a}} Some cases may be still under investigation and county not assigned yet.\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.healthvermont.gov/covid Information] from the State of Vermont Department of Health\n* [https://vtpsd.maps.arcgis.com/apps/webappviewer/index.html?id=c926d155167d4a5586e8e1aca1701cfa List of Wi-Fi Internet hot spots in Vermont open during COVID-19 pandemic]\n* [https://www.vermont.gov/volunteer Volunteer site - Help Support Vermonters Affected by COVID-19]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Vermont]]\n[[Category:2020 in Vermont]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Vermont]]\n[[Category:Health in Vermont]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in Vermont, United States}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Vermont\n| map1            = \n| places          = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Vermont]]\n| first_case      = [[Bennington, Vermont|Bennington]]<ref name=\"vtdigger20200307\" />\n| arrival_date    = March 7, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=8|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 338\n| deaths          = 17\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://www.healthvermont.gov/covid}}\n}}\nThe 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Vermont]] is part of an ongoing worldwide [[Viral disease|viral]] [[pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] ({{nowrap|COVID-19}}), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus&nbsp;2]] ({{nowrap|SARS-CoV-2}}).\n{{2019\u201320_coronavirus_pandemic_data/United_States/Vermont_medical_cases_chart}}\n\n==Timeline==\nThe [[Vermont Department of Health|Vermont Department of Heath]] announced the state's first case of COVID-19 on Saturday, March 7, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lamdin |first1=Courtney |title=Vermont Health Department Reports the State's First Coronavirus Case |url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/OffMessage/archives/2020/03/07/vermont-health-department-reports-the-states-first-coronavirus-case|url-status=live |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=SevenDays VT |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> The patient was subsequently identified as being in a [[Southwestern Vermont Medical Center|hospital]] in Bennington, Vermont.<ref name=\"vtdigger20200307\">{{cite news |last1=Walters |first1=John |title=Bennington patient Vermont's first 'presumptive positive' coronavirus case |url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/07/vermont-has-first-presumptive-case-of-coronavirus/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=VTDigger |date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, the first two deaths from COVID-19 were announced, one a male in [[White River Junction, Vermont|White River Junction]] and the other a female in [[Burlington, Vermont|Burlington]]. Both were over 80 years old.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Landen|first1=Xander|url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/19/two-die-from-coronavirus-infections-in-vermont/|title=Two die from coronavirus infections in Vermont|date=19 March 2020|work=VTDigger|accessdate=20 March 2020|url-status=live|last2=Jickling|first2=Katie}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, it was announced that three more people had died at a Burlington nursing home, bringing the statewide total to five deaths from COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lamdin |first1=Courtney |title=Three More Dead of Coronavirus at Burlington Nursing Home |url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/OffMessage/archives/2020/03/23/four-people-dead-of-coronavirus-at-burlington-nursing-home |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Seven Days VT |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, the Vermont Department of Health announced two more deaths, including one more at a Burlington nursing home where four other residents have died from COVID-19. The state also announced they have tested 1,535 samples since March 7, and have increased the testing capacity across the state.<ref name=\"sevendaysvt-20200324\">{{cite news |last1=Kamdin |first1=Courtney |title=Vermont Reports Two More Deaths as Coronavirus Cases Climb |url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/OffMessage/archives/2020/03/24/vermont-reports-two-more-deaths-as-coronavirus-cases-climb |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=SevenDaysVT |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, the eighth death in Vermont was announced, again of a resident at the same Burlington nursing home where five other residents have died.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Flanders |first1=Colin |title=Vermont Seeing 'Exponential Growth' of Coronavirus |url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/OffMessage/archives/2020/03/25/vermont-seeing-exponential-growth-of-coronavirus |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Seven Days VT |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, the Vermont Department of Health reported 37 new confirmed cases, the most reported in a single day, with the number of deaths rising to 13.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Flanders |first1=Colin |title=Vermont Announces 37 More Coronavirus Cases, One New Death |url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/OffMessage/archives/2020/03/31/vermont-announces-37-more-coronavirus-cases-one-new-death |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=Seven Days VT |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Economic and social effects==\n\n===Schools closed===\n\nAll schools were ordered to be closed for in-person classes as of Wednesday, March 18, until at least April 6, 2020.<ref name=\"vtdigger20200315\" /> On March 26, this closure was extended through the rest of the academic year.<ref name=\"vt-state-directive-5\" />\n\nOn March 23, the [[University of Vermont]] declared that all students must leave the UVM campus by March 30, except for those approved for emergency housing. Courses will be taught online for the remainder of the semester. UVM officials also indicated they will make a decision about canceling UVM's commencement ceremony by the end of March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Galloway |first1=Anne |title=UVM sends students home |url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/23/uvm-sends-students-home/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=VTDigger |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Restaurants and bars closed===\n\nBars and restaurants were ordered to close by 2:00pm on Tuesday, March 17, and to remain closed until April 6. Restaurants were allowed to continue providing takeout and delivery service.<ref name=\"vtdigger20200316-bars\">{{cite news |last1=Wallace Allen |first1=Anne |title=Bars and restaurants in Vermont will be ordered closed at 2 p.m. Tuesday: Scott admin |url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/16/bars-and-restaurants-in-vermont-will-be-ordered-closed-at-2-p-m-tuesday-scott-admin/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=VTDigger |date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> All gyms, spas, hair salons and tattoo parlors were ordered closed as of 8:00pm on March 23, 2020.<ref name=\"vtdigger20200321\" />\n\n=== Impact on media ===\n\nOn March 17, the publisher of three newspapers in southern Vermont, [[Brattleboro Reformer]], [[Bennington Banner]] and [[Manchester Journal]] indicated that all full-time staff members would be furloughed for one of the next five weeks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Heintz |first1=Paul |title=Media Note: Vermont News Outlets Ramp Up as Outbreak Threatens Business |url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/OffMessage/archives/2020/03/19/media-note-vermont-news-outlets-ramp-up-as-outbreak-threatens-business |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=Seven Days VT |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, the [[Barre Montpelier Times Argus|''Barre Montpelier Times Argu''s]] and ''[[Rutland Herald]]'' newspapers announced that due to the financial impact of the pandemic they would be reducing their print publishing to three days a week and temporarily laying off 20 staffpeople.<ref name=\"times-argus-20200322\">{{cite news |last1=Pappas |first1=Steve |title=City Room: COVID-19's effects on us |url=https://www.timesargus.com/news/covid19/city-room-covid--s-effects-on-us/article_35074189-82f9-5fbd-b695-ef5cc3f5751a.html|url-status=live |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Times Argus |publisher=Brunswick Publishing LLC |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, ''[[Seven Days (newspaper)|Seven Days]]'' indicated they would lay off seven employees.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Heintz |first1=Paul |title=Media Note: Seven Days Lays Off Seven Employees |url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/OffMessage/archives/2020/03/23/media-note-seven-days-lays-off-seven-employees |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=Seven Days |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government response==\nOn March 10, the Vermont State Emergency Operations Center was activated.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://vem.vermont.gov/news/governor-phil-scott-orders-activation-state-emergency-operations-center|title=Governor Phil Scott Orders Activation of State Emergency Operations Center|date=2020-03-10|website=Vermont Emergency Management}}</ref> On March 13, a COVID-19 task force was set up<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://vem.vermont.gov/news/governor-phil-scott-details-development-covid-19-task-force|title=Governor Phil Scott Details Development of COVID-19 Task Force|website=Vermont Emergency Management|date=2020-03-02}}</ref> and  Governor [[Phil Scott (politician)|Phil Scott]] issued Executive Order 01-20 which declared a State of Emergency until it expires on April 15.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/OffMessage/archives/2020/03/13/governor-scott-declares-state-of-emergency-in-vermont|title=Scott Declares State of Emergency in Vermont|newspaper=Seven Days|date=2020-03-13|first=Colin|last=Flanders}}</ref> The Executive Order limits visitors to nursing homes, assisted living residences, residential care homes, and specific care facilities.  It also suspends traveling by state employees for non-essential government business, prohibits most mass gatherings including at schools and excluding transit, most offices, and grocery and commercial stores.  The [[Vermont National Guard|National Guard]] was also activated.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://governor.vermont.gov/content/declaration-state-emergency-response-covid-19-and-national-guard-call-out-executive-order-01|title=DECLARATION OF STATE OF EMERGENCY IN RESPONSE TO COVID-19 AND NATIONAL GUARD CALL-OUT (EXECUTIVE ORDER 01-20)]|website=Office of Governor Phil Scott}}</ref> Additionally, the [[Vermont General Assembly]] voted to adjourn until March 24 to prepare for the virus.<ref>[https://www.wcax.com/content/news/Vermont-statehouse-to-adjourn--568770941.html Vermont Statehouse to temporarily shut down next week] [[WCAX]]</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Governor Phil Scott ordered all schools in Vermont to be closed and all school activities to be cancelled no later than Wednesday, March 18, and lasting through at least April 6.<ref name=\"vtdigger20200315\">{{cite news|last1=Duffort|first1=Lola|url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/15/scott-orders-schools-to-close/|title=Scott orders schools to close|date=2020-03-15|work=VTDigger|accessdate=16 March 2020|url-status=live|publisher=|last2=Galloway|first2=Anne}}</ref><ref name=\"stateofvt-scott-school-closure\">{{cite web |title=Gov. Scott Orders Orderly Closure of Vermont preK-12 Schools This Week |url=https://governor.vermont.gov/press-release/gov-scott-orders-orderly-closure-vermont-prek-12-schools-week |website=Office of Governor Phil Scott |publisher=State of Vermont |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> On March 16, Governor Scott announced his emergency declaration would be amended to limit public gatherings to either 50 people or 50% occupancy.<ref name=\"vtdigger20200316-50\">{{cite news |last1=Katie Jickling |first1=Lola Duffort |title=Update: Vermont now up to 12 cases as Scott limits gatherings to 50 |url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/16/vermont-now-up-to-12-coronavirus-cases-scott-administration-says/ |accessdate=16 March 2020 |publisher=VT Digger |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> Also on March 16, Burlington Mayor [[Miro Weinberger]] declared a state of emergency for Burlington and ordered all bars and restaurants to close Tuesday starting at 6:00am and continuing for at least 24 hours. All nonessential city services will also be suspended from Wednesday, March 18, through at least April 6.<ref>{{cite news |title=Burlington restaurants, bars to close for 24 hours |url=https://www.wcax.com/content/news/Burlington-restaurants-bars-to-close-for-24-hours-568839021.html |accessdate=16 March 2020 |publisher=WCAX |date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Miro Weinberger Declares Emergency and Announces New City Actions in Response to COVID-19 |url=https://www.burlingtonvt.gov/Press/mayor-miro-weinberger-declares-emergency-and-announces-new-city-actions-in-response-to-covid |website=City of Burlington |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Governor Scott ordered the closure of all Vermont child care programs, except for those that serve people \"essential\" to responding to the pandemic.<ref name=\"bfp-20200318\">{{cite news |last1=McCullum |first1=April |title=Gov. Scott orders closure of child care programs not serving 'essential' workers |url=https://www.burlingtonfreepress.com/story/news/local/vermont/2020/03/17/vermont-gov-phil-scott-order-child-care-closures-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/5073017002/ |accessdate=18 March 2020 |publisher=Burlington Free Press |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> The closure starts on Wednesday, March 18, and lasts through April 6. The governor's order defines \"essential\" persons as healthcare providers, criminal justice personnel; public health employees; firefighters; Vermont National Guard personnel; other first responders and state employees; and staff and providers of necessary childcare services.<ref name=\"scott-20200317\">{{cite web |title=Governor Phil Scott Orders Implementation Of Child Care System For Personnel Essential To Covid-19 Response - Childcare Centers Closed; Urged to Provide Care for Children of Vermonters Responding to Crisis |url=https://governor.vermont.gov/press-release/governor-phil-scott-orders-implementation-child-care-system-personnel-essential-covid |website=Office of Governor Phil Scott |publisher=State of Vermont |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Governor Scott announced that he would be working with the VT state legislature to develop a loan program through the Vermont Economic Development Authority (VEDA) for businesses impacted economically by the pandemic.<ref name=\"vtdigger20200320\">{{cite news |last1=Landen |first1=Xander |title=Scott says he's not considering shelter in place order at this time |url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/20/scott-says-hes-not-considering-shelter-in-place-order-at-this-time/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |publisher=VTDigger |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> He also announced that Vermont businesses can apply for economic injury disaster loans through the [[Small Business Administration]] (SBA).<ref name=\"philscott20200320\">{{cite web |title=Governor Phil Scott Announces Economic Injury Disaster Loans Available to Small Businesses Affected by COVID-19 |url=https://governor.vermont.gov/press-release/governor-phil-scott-announces-economic-injury-disaster-loans-available-small |website=Office of Governor Phil Scott |publisher=State of Vermont |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> The Vermont Senate will reconvene on Tuesday, March 24, to act on measures to respond to COVID-19.<ref name=\"vtdigger20200320-senate\">{{cite news |last1=Xander Landen |first1=Kit Norten |title=Senate to return to the Statehouse next week to pass COVID-19 measures |url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/20/senate-to-return-to-the-statehouse-next-week-to-pass-covid-19-measures/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |publisher=VTDigger |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Vermont state officials also stated that the number of available beds statewide has increased to 500 and the number of available ventilators has increased to 240.<ref name=\"sevendaysvt-20200320\">{{cite news |last1=Flanders |first1=Colin |title=Bracing for Coronavirus Spread, Vermont Frees Up Hospital Beds |url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/OffMessage/archives/2020/03/20/bracing-for-coronavirus-spread-vermont-frees-up-hospital-beds |accessdate=20 March 2020 |publisher=SevenDays VT |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, Governor Scott ordered the closure of gyms and similar exercise facilities, hair salons, spas and tattoo parlors by 8 pm on March 23. He also extended his earlier executive order to restrict gatherings to no more than 10 people.<ref name=\"vtdigger20200321\">{{cite news |last1=Allen |first1=Anne Wallace |title=Scott orders gyms, salons closed; limits gatherings to no more than 10 |url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/21/scott-orders-gyms-salons-closed-limits-gatherings-to-no-more-than-10/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=VTDigger |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> On March 23, Governor Scott ordered the [[Vermont National Guard]] and the Vermont Emergency Operations Center to set up a medical \"surge site\" to respond to COVID-19 cases.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Galloway |first1=Anne |title=Three more die at Burlington Health and Rehab of COVID-19 |url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/23/three-more-die-at-burlington-health-and-rehab-of-covid-19/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=VTDigger |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Governor Scott also announced that the Vermont Department of Public Service released a [https://publicservice.vermont.gov/announcements/public-wifi-hotspots-vermont \"Public Wi-Fi Hot Spot Map\"] to enable people in Vermont to find places to access the Internet for free.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://governor.vermont.gov/press-release/governor-phil-scott-announces-wi-fi-hot-spot-map|title=Governor Phil Scott Announces Public Service Department Wi-Fi Hot Spot Map to Help Vermonters Access Internet During COVID-19|website=State of Vermont - Office of Governor Phil Scott|date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, Governor Scott issued a \"Stay Home, Stay Safe\" order directing all residents of Vermont to stay home \"leaving only for essential reasons, critical to health and safety.\" The order directs that all businesses and not-for-profit entities must suspend all in-person business operations, except for specific exemptions. The order will remain in effect until April 15, 2020, unless extended or shortened.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://governor.vermont.gov/press-release/governor-phil-scott-issues-%E2%80%9Cstay-home-stay-safe%E2%80%9D-order-directs-additional-closures|title=GOVERNOR PHIL SCOTT ISSUES A \"STAY HOME, STAY SAFE\" ORDER, DIRECTS ADDITIONAL CLOSURES|website=Office of Governor Phil Scott}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Meyn |first1=Colin |title=\"Stay home,\" Scott orders in response to COVID-19 outbreak in Vermont |url=https://vtdigger.org/2020/03/24/stay-home-scott-orders-in-response-to-covid-19-outbreak-in-vermont/ |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=VTDigger |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> On March 26, Governor Scott ordered all schools in Vermont to remain closed for in-person classes for the rest of the academic year. School districts have until April 13 to produce distance learning plans for the remainder of the school year.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reed |first1=Elodie |last2=Elder-Connors |first2=Liam |title=Gov. Closes Vermont Schools For Rest Of Academic Year |url=https://www.vpr.org/post/gov-closes-vermont-schools-rest-academic-year |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=Vermont Public Radio |date=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vt-state-directive-5\">{{cite web |title=Directive 5 - Continuity of Learning Planning (Pursuant to EO 01-20) |url=https://governor.vermont.gov/content/directive-5-continuity-learning-planning-pursuant-eo-01-20 |website=Office of Governor Phil Scott |publisher=State of Vermont |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, Governor Scott imposed quarantine restrictions on travelers arriving in Vermont.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vpr.org/post/governor-orders-14-day-quarantine-out-state-travelers|title=Governor Orders 14-Day Quarantine For Out-Of-State Travelers|last=Giles|first=Mark Davis, Abagael|website=www.vpr.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> On March 31, the Vermont Agency of Commerce and Community Development ordered large retailers \"to cease in-person sales of non-essential items in order to reduce the number of people coming into the stores.\" The agency also ordered stores to close showrooms and garden sections of home improvement centers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Asch |first1=Sarah |title=Vermont orders big retailers to cease in-person sales on non-essential items |url=https://vtdigger.org/liveblog/vermont-orders-big-retailers-to-cease-in-person-sales-on-non-essential-items/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=VTDigger |date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Also, Governor Phil Scott announced the launch of a new website - [https://www.vermont.gov/volunteer https://www.vermont.gov/volunteer] - where Vermonters can sign up to volunteer to help in the state's response to COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Asch |first1=Sarah |title=Governor calls on Vermonters to pitch in with COVID-19 response |url=https://vtdigger.org/liveblog/governor-calls-on-vermonters-to-pitch-in-with-covid-19-response/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=VTDigger |date=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Governor Scott Calls on Vermonters to Support COVID-19 Response |url=https://governor.vermont.gov/press-release/governor-scott-calls-vermonters-to-service |website=Office of Governor Phil Scott |publisher=State of Vermont |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, Governor Scott announced that the State, in anticipation of a surge in COVID-19 cases, was preparing two additional medical surge locations in partnership with the Vermont National Guard: a 400-bed location at the Champlain Valley Exposition in [[Essex Junction, Vermont|Essex Junction]], and a 150-bed location in [[Rutland County, Vermont|Rutland County]]. Additional rapid reaction medical surge trailers, each containing materials for 50 additional beds, had been prepositioned throughout the state to facilitate rapid deployment. Additional assets, including two state portable hospitals, were also being prepared. These measures are a continuation in the State\u2019s plan to prevent hospitals from exceeding their capacities in the event of a surge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://governor.vermont.gov/press-release/governor-phil-scott-announces-additional-medical-surge-locations|title=Governor Phil Scott Announces Additional Medical Surge Locations|last=|first=|date=|website=Office of Governor Phil Scott|publisher=State of Vermont|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Vermont<ref name=\"vt-doh-covid\">{{cite web |title=Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) |url=https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/infectious-disease/2019-novel-coronavirus |website=Department of Health |publisher=State of Vermont |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\nUpdated April 2, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Addison\n|26\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Bennington\n|17\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Caledonia\n|4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Chittenden\n|177\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Essex\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Franklin\n|16\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Grand Isle\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Lamoille\n|14\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Orange\n|4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Orleans\n|7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Rutland\n|12\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Washington\n|18\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Windham\n|18\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Windsor\n|20\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |''N/A''{{ref label|unassigned|a