in Wales: First Covid-19 death confirmed |work=BBC News |date=16 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316140423/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51909109 |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, the [[Welsh Government]] announced that all schools in Wales would be closing by 20 March. With a limited number of schools remaining open to provide support for key workers and children with additional needs. <ref>{{cite news |title=All schools in Wales to close by Friday |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51947148 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318132314/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51947148 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> It was further announced in the following days that all exams, including GCSEs and A-Levels, would be cancelled, with grades being based on existing work and predicted grades. <ref name=\"Coronavirus: How Wales' approach differs from England\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: How Wales' approach differs from England |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52094944 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, it was revealed that around 75 officers at [[HMP Berwyn]] in [[Wrexham County Borough]] were off work due to sickness or self-isolation, and 22 prisoners showing symptoms of coronavirus were being isolated by the prison. However, the prison had enough staff members to remain fully operational.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rees |first1=Jenny |title=Seventy-five prison officers off sick or isolating |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51966387 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320154011/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51966387 |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, along with the rest of the [[United Kingdom]], Wales banned gatherings of two or more people, except individuals in the same household. Pubs, restaurants (with exception for take-aways) and shops selling 'non-essential goods' were ordered to closed. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52014472|title=Coronavirus: UK brings in strict curbs on life to fight virus|work=BBC News|date=24 March 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> The measures in place that control exercise outside the home differ from those in England, where the measures in place do not stipulate that once-a-day restriction, the Welsh version do specifically limit exercise outside the home to once a day, with a maximum fine of \u00a3120, compared to \u00a3960 in England. <ref name=\"Coronavirus: How Wales' approach differs from England\" />\n\nOn 27 March, it was announced that the [[Millennium Stadium|Principality Stadium]] in [[Cardiff]] was to be used as a field hospital for up to 2,000 beds. It was also announced that other rugby stadiums throughout Wales, including [[Parc y Scarlets]] would also be made available.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/52024970|title=Coronavirus: Principality Stadium to be used as 2000-bed hospital|work=BBC Sport|date=27 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, a \u00a31.1 billion support package for businesses and public services affected by the pandemic, included a \u00a3500 million ''economy crisis fund'', \u00a3100 million in loans, and \u00a3400 million in emergency funding.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52085642|title=Coronavirus: Welsh Government announces \u00a31.1bn funding|work=BBC News|date=30 March 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, three inmates at [[HMP Swansea]] had been confirmed as testing positive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-wales-52091590?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e839f5aa8854e067111aa04%26Three%20Swansea%20prisoners%20test%20positive%262020-03-31T21%3A04%3A55.522Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:077f9811-446c-452b-9773-f0a001e984af&pinned_post_asset_id=5e839f5aa8854e067111aa04&pinned_post_type=share|title=Three Swansea prisoners test positive|work=BBC News|date=31 March 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 === \nOn 1 April, it was announced that during the pandemic home abortions would be allowed for women in the first nine weeks of pregnancy, following an online or telephone consultation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52118335|title=Coronavirus: Home abortions allowed in Wales during pandemic|work=BBC News|date=1 April 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 2 April, it was announced that the number of confirmed cases had risen above 2,000 and the number deaths in Wales had risen above 100.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://covid19-phwstatement.nhs.wales/|title=Public Health Wales statement on Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak|work=Public Health Wales|date=2 April 2020|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> Virtual GP appointments were also rolled out across Wales, allowing for phone consultations, with video consultations also available if needed. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gov.wales/virtual-doctor-appointments-rolled-out-across-wales|title=Virtual doctor appointments rolled out across Wales|work=Welsh Government|date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April it was announced that a two metre social distancing guidance would become law.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-wales-52134730?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e872ac9cfdb750670d9bdd8%26Social%20distancing%20%27to%20become%20law%27%262020-04-03T12%3A52%3A33.478Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:e114f45f-d854-4f9b-b05e-22c6236c1357&pinned_post_asset_id=5e872ac9cfdb750670d9bdd8&pinned_post_type=share\n|title=Social distancing 'to become law'|work=BBC News|date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> The Welsh Government also announced that it would provide financial assistance to [[Cardiff Airport]], to maintain solvency during reduced operations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gov.wales/welsh-government-steps-short-term-funding-support-cardiff-airport-and-calls-change-approach|title=Welsh Government steps in with short-term funding support for Cardiff Airport and calls for change of approach from Westminster|work=Welsh Government|date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics == \n{{Template:2019-20 coronavirus pandemic data/Wales medical cases chart}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n'''Situation on 3 April 2020''' <ref name=\"PublicHealthWales\" />\n! Health Board\n! Number of Cases\n|-\n| [[Aneurin Bevan University Health Board|Aneurin Bevan]]\n| 867\n|-\n| [[Betsi Cadwaladr University Health Board|Betsi Cadwaladr]]\n| 133\n|-\n| [[Cardiff and Vale University Health Board|Cardiff and Vale]]\n| 613\n|-\n| [[Cwm Taf Morgannwg University Health Board|Cwm Taf Morgannwg]]\n| 329\n|-\n| [[Hywel Dda University Health Board|Hywel Dda]]\n| 144\n|-\n| [[Powys Teaching Health Board|Powys]]\n| 41\n|-\n| [[Swansea Bay University Health Board|Swansea Bay]]\n| 273\n|-\n| Welsh resident outside of Wales\n| 21\n|-\n| Location not confirmed  \n| 43\n|-\n| '''Total''' \n| '''2466'''\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|Wales]]\n[[Category:2020 in Wales]]\n[[Category:Health in Wales]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApril 2020:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: two metre \u2192 two-metre", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Wales"}
{"title_page": "2009 in UFC", "text_new": "{{short description|UFC MMA events in 2009}}\n{{Year in UFC\n|name = 2009 in UFC\n|image = Logo of the Ultimate Fighting Championship.svg\n|image_size = 176px\n|first_date = January 17, 2009\n|last_date = December 12, 2009\n|total_events = 20\n|numbered_events = 15\n|fight_night_events = 3\n|tuf_finale_events = 2\n|total_fights = 215\n|title_fights = 11\n|preceded_by = [[2008 in UFC]]\n|followed_by = [[2010 in UFC]]\n}}\n\nThe year '''2009''' is the 17th year in the history of the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC), a [[mixed martial arts]] promotion based in the United States. In 2009 the UFC held 20 events beginning with, ''UFC 93: Franklin vs. Henderson''.\n\n{{TOClimit|2}}\n\n==Title fights==\n{{MMAtitle}}\n{{MMAtitle card|[[List of UFC champions|Title fights in 2009]]}}\n{{MMAtitle bout\n| Welterweight\n| [[Georges St-Pierre]] (c)\n| def.\n| [[B.J. Penn]]\n| TKO (corner stoppage)\n| 4\n| 5:00\n| [[UFC 94]]\n| For the [[UFC Welterweight Championship]].\n}}\n{{MMAtitle bout\n| Middleweight\n| [[Anderson Silva]] (c)\n| def.\n| [[Thales Leites]]\n| Decision (unanimous) (49-46, 48-47, 50-46)\n| 5\n| 5:00\n| [[UFC 97]]\n| For the [[UFC Middleweight Championship]].\n}}\n{{MMAtitle bout\n| Light Heavyweight\n| [[Lyoto Machida]]\n| def.\n| [[Rashad Evans]] (c)\n| KO (punches)\n| 2\n| 3:57\n| [[UFC 98]]\n| For the [[UFC Light Heavyweight Championship]].\n}}\n{{MMAtitle bout\n| Welterweight\n| [[Georges St-Pierre]] (c)\n| def.\n| [[Thiago Alves (fighter)|Thiago Alves]]\n| Decision (unanimous) (50\u201345, 50\u201344, 50\u201345)\n| 5\n| 5:00\n| [[UFC 100]]\n| For the [[UFC Welterweight Championship]].\n}}\n{{MMAtitle bout\n| Heavyweight\n| [[Brock Lesnar]] (c)\n| def.\n| [[Frank Mir]] (ic)\n| TKO (punches)\n| 2\n| 1:48\n| [[UFC 100]]\n| [[UFC Heavyweight Championship]] unification bout.\n}}\n{{MMAtitle bout\n| Lightweight\n| [[B.J. Penn]] (c)\n| def\n| [[Kenny Florian]]\n| Submission (rear-naked choke)\n| 4\n| 3:54\n| [[UFC