-record-355-million-live-gate.mma |title=UFC 101 draws 17,411 attendance for Pennsylvania state record $3.55 million live gate |publisher=mmajunkie.com |date=Aug 9, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090812095412/http://mmajunkie.com/news/15778/ufc-101-draws-17411-attendance-for-state-record-355-million-live-gate.mma |archivedate=2009-08-12 }}</ref>\n|-\n|133\n|[[UFC 100]]\n|{{dts|2009|Jul|11}}\n|[[Mandalay Bay Events Center]]\n|[[Las Vegas]], U.S.\n|{{nts|10871}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fiveouncesofpain.com/2009/07/21/ufc-100-draws-live-gate-of-5128490/|title=UFC 100 draws live gate of $5,128,490|publisher=fiveouncesofpain.com|date=Jul 21, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n|132\n|{{sort|Ultimate Fighter 09|[[The Ultimate Fighter: United States vs. United Kingdom Finale]]}}\n|{{dts|2009|Jun|20}}\n|[[Palms Casino Resort]]\n|[[Las Vegas]], U.S.\n|{{nts|2217}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/15354/the-ultimate-fighter-9-finale-nabs-2217-attendees-for-a-500k-gate.mma |title=The Ultimate Fighter 9 Finale nabs 2,217 attendees for a $500K gate |publisher=mmajunkie.com |date=Jun 29, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023013929/http://mmajunkie.com/news/15354/the-ultimate-fighter-9-finale-nabs-2217-attendees-for-a-500k-gate.mma |archivedate=2012-10-23 }}</ref>\n|-\n|131\n|{{sort|UFC 099|[[UFC 99|UFC 99: The Comeback]]}}\n|{{dts|2009|Jun|13}}\n|[[Lanxess Arena]]\n|[[Cologne]], Germany\n|{{nts|12854}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/15190/ufc-99-draws-reported-12800-spectators-for-1-3-million-live-gate.mma|title=UFC 99 draws reported 12,800 spectators for $1.3 million live gate in Cologne, Germany|publisher=mmajunkie.com|date=Jun 13, 2009|access-date=2015-03-04|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120630015418/mmajunkie.com/news/15190/ufc-99-draws-reported-12800-spectators-for-1-3-million-live-gate.mma|archive-date=2012-06-30|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|130\n|{{sort|UFC 098|[[UFC 98|UFC 98: Evans vs. Machida]]}}\n|{{dts|2009|May|23}}\n|[[MGM Grand Garden Arena]]\n|[[Las Vegas]], U.S.\n|{{nts|12606}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/14973/ufc-98-in-las-vegas-delivers-12606-spectators-and-3-4-million-gate.mma|title=UFC 98 in Las Vegas delivers 12,606 spectators and $3.4 million gate|publisher=mmajunkie.com|date=May 24, 2009|access-date=2015-03-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023013941/http://mmajunkie.com/news/14973/ufc-98-in-las-vegas-delivers-12606-spectators-and-3-4-million-gate.mma|archive-date=2012-10-23|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|129\n|{{sort|UFC 097|[[UFC 97|UFC 97: Redemption]]}}\n|{{dts|2009|Apr|18}}\n|[[Bell Centre]]\n|[[Montreal|Montreal, Quebec]], Canada\n|{{nts|21451}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/14626/ufc-97-sets-new-north-american-mma-record-with-21451-attendance.mma|title=UFC 97 sets new North American MMA attendance record with 21,451|publisher=mmajunkie.com|date=Apr 19, 2009|access-date=2015-03-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023014056/http://mmajunkie.com/news/14626/ufc-97-sets-new-north-american-mma-record-with-21451-attendance.mma|archive-date=2012-10-23|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|128\n|{{sort|UFC Fight Night 18|[[UFC Fight Night: Condit vs. Kampmann]]}}\n|{{dts|2009|Apr|1}}\n|[[Sommet Center]]\n|[[Nashville, Tennessee]], U.S.\n|{{nts|10267}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/14438/ufcs-tennessee-debut-sets-ufc-fight-night-attendance-record.mma |title=UFC's Tennessee debut sets UFC Fight Night attendance record |publisher=mmajunkie.com |date=Apr 2, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023022044/http://mmajunkie.com/news/14438/ufcs-tennessee-debut-sets-ufc-fight-night-attendance-record.mma |archivedate=2012-10-23 }}</ref>\n|-\n|127\n|{{sort|UFC 096|[[UFC 96|UFC 96: Jackson vs. Jardine]]}}\n|{{dts|2009|Mar|7}}\n|[[Nationwide Arena]]\n|[[Columbus, Ohio]], U.S.\n|{{nts|17033}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/14204/ufc-96-draws-17033-spectators-for-a-1-8-million-gate.mma|title=UFC 96 draws 17,033 spectators for a $1.8 million gate|publisher=mmajunkie.com|date=Mar 8, 2009|access-date=2015-03-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023022133/http://mmajunkie.com/news/14204/ufc-96-draws-17033-spectators-for-a-1-8-million-gate.mma|archive-date=2012-10-23|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|126\n|{{sort|UFC 095|[[UFC 95|UFC 95: Sanchez vs. Stevenson]]}}\n|{{dts|2009|Feb|21}}\n|[[The O2 Arena|The O<sub>2</sub> arena]]\n|London, England, U.K.\n|{{nts|13268}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmaweekly.com/blog/2009/02/ufc-95-delivers-1-million-us-and-strong.asp |title=UFC 95 delivers 1 million U.S. and strong |publisher=mmaweekly.com |date=Feb 23, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225184401/http://www.mmaweekly.com/blog/2009/02/ufc-95-delivers-1-million-us-and-strong.asp |archivedate=2009-02-25 }}</ref>\n|-\n|125\n|{{sort|UFC Fight Night 17|[[UFC Fight Night: Lauzon vs. Stephens]]}}\n|{{dts|2009|Feb|7}}\n|[[USF Sun Dome]]\n|[[Tampa, Florida]], U.S.\n|{{nts|7596}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/13947/ufc-fight-night-17-draws-7596-for-428k-live-gate.mma|title=UFC Fight Night 17 draws 7,596 for $428k live gate|publisher=mmajunkie.com|date=Feb 8, 2009|access-date=2015-03-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022024656/http://mmajunkie.com/news/13947/ufc-fight-night-17-draws-7596-for-428k-live-gate.mma|archive-date=2012-10-22|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|124\n|{{sort|UFC 094|[[UFC 94|UFC 94: St-Pierre vs. Penn 2]]}}\n|{{dts|2009|Jan|31}}\n|[[MGM Grand Garden Arena]]\n|[[Las Vegas]], U.S.\n|{{nts|14885}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/14028/ufc-94-officially-draws-14885-for-4-29-million-gate-according-to-nsac.mma|title=UFC 94 officially draws 14,885 for $4.29 million gate according to NSAC|publisher=mmajunkie.com|access-date=2015-03-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023022139/http://mmajunkie.com/news/14028/ufc-94-officially-draws-14885-for-4-29-million-gate-according-to-nsac.mma|archive-date=2012-10-23|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|123\n|{{sort|UFC 093|[[UFC 93|UFC 93: Franklin vs. Henderson]]}}\n|{{dts|2009|Jan|17}}\n|[[The O2 (Dublin)|The O<sub>2</sub>]]\n|[[Dublin]], Ireland\n|{{nts|9369}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/13750/ufc-93-draws-9369-attendees-for-1-3-million-gate.mma|title=UFC 93 draws 6,369 attendees for $1.3 million gate|publisher=mmajunkie.com|date=Jan 18, 2009|access-date=2015-03-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021033912/http://mmajunkie.com/news/13750/ufc-93-draws-9369-attendees-for-1-3-million-gate.mma|archive-date=2012-10-21|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]]\n* [[List of UFC champions]]\n* [[List of UFC events]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{UFC Events}}\n\n[[Category:Years in Ultimate Fighting Championship]]\n[[Category:2009 in mixed martial arts]]\n", "name_user": "Deancarmeli", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2009_in_UFC"}
{"title_page": "Drogheda United F.C.", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish association football club}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname    = Drogheda United\n| image       = Drogheda United FC.svg\n| image_size  = 200px\n| fullname    = Drogheda United Football Club\n| nickname    = The Drogs, \nClaret and Blue Army\n| founded     = 1919 (as Drogheda United)<br>1975 (merged with Drogheda F.C.)<ref name=\"Local soccer clubs merge to form new Drogheda United\">{{cite news|title=Local soccer clubs merge to form new Drogheda United|url=http://www.independent.ie/regionals/droghedaindependent/lifestyle/local-soccer-clubs-merge-to-form-new-drogheda-united-27166586.html|accessdate=16 May 2012|newspaper=Drogheda Independent|date=1975}}</ref> \n| ground      = [[United Park]], [[Drogheda]], County Louth\n| capacity    = 3,500\n| current = 2020 League of Ireland First Division\n| owner       = Supporter owned\n| chairman    = Conor Hoey\n| manager     = [[Tim Clancy]]\n| league      = [[League of Ireland First Division]]\n| season      = [[2020 League of Ireland First Division|2020]]\n| position    = TBC\n| website     = http://www.droghedaunited.ie\n|\n| pattern_la1 = _drogheda19h\n| pattern_b1  = _drogheda19h\n| pattern_ra1 = _drogheda19h\n| body1       = \n| pattern_so1 = FFFFFF\n| leftarm1    = 97CBFF\n| rightarm1   = 97CBFF\n| shorts1     = 80BFFF\n| socks1      = 80BFFF\n|\n| pattern_b2  = _drogheda20a\n| leftarm2    = FFFFFF\n| body2       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm2   = FFFFFF\n| shorts2     = 771F35\n| socks2      = 771F35\n| pattern_la3 = \n| pattern_b3  = \n| pattern_ra3 = \n| shorts3     = 80BFFF\n| socks3      = 80BFFF\n|\n}}\n'''Drogheda United Football Club''' ({{lang-ga|Cumann Peile Dhroichead \u00c1tha Aontaithe}}) is an [[List of association football clubs in the Republic of Ireland|Irish association football club]] based in [[Drogheda]], County Louth playing in the [[League of Ireland First Division]]. They play their home matches at [[United Park]].\n\nThe current club is the amalgamation of two former clubs in the town: Drogheda United, a non-league club founded in 1919; and Drogheda F.C., founded in 1962. The clubs merged their operations to form the current club in 1975 and have achieved success since 2005 by winning two [[Setanta Sports Cup]]s, an [[FAI Cup]], and their first league title, the [[2007 League of Ireland]].\n\n== History ==\n\n=== 1919\u20131975: Early years ===\nFounded in 1919 the original Drogheda United were a non-league club for all of their early years of existence but on Saturday 22 June 1963 another Drogheda Club \u2013 '''Drogheda F.C.''' (founded in 1962) were elected to the [[League of Ireland]] when the league was expanded to include twelve teams rather than ten. In their first season there they finished tenth and also in each of the next three seasons finished in the bottom three. In the 1967\u201368 season they achieved a respectable fifth-place finish and the following season finished in sixth place. When the league expanded to include fourteen teams the club dropped down the table again finishing in the bottom five in each of the next six seasons and also recording their heaviest league defeat 8\u20131 to [[Cork Hibernians F.C.|Cork Hibernians]] in the 1970\u201371 season. They did, however, get to [[FAI Cup]] final that season where they were beaten 3\u20130 by [[Limerick F.C.|Limerick]] in a replay after the first match ended 00..\n\n=== 1975\u20132003 ===\nIn 1975 Drogheda F.C. amalgamated with Drogheda United to form Drogheda United F.C. and the 1975\u201376 season saw an improvement in fortunes on the field as they finished sixth in the league and they also reached the FAI Cup Final for the second time, this time losing 1\u20130 to [[Bohemian F.C.|Bohemians]]. For the next three seasons, quite the opposite at what had happened before, they finished in third place. During these seasons Drogheda United also achieved two club records \u2013 their biggest league victory (7\u20131 v [[Finn Harps F.C.|Finn Harps]]) and [[Cathal Muckian]] scoring 21 league goals in a season. The club then endured another tough spell in the league finishing in the bottom half for the next five seasons bar the 1982\u201383 season when they managed to achieve their second highest ever league placing of second-place (they later won the league in 2007) finishing sixteen points behind [[Athlone Town A.F.C.|Athlone Town]]. They did win their first ever trophy during these seasons also, the [[League of Ireland Cup]] in the 1983\u201384 season.\n\nThe 1984\u201385 season saw the introduction of the [[League of Ireland First Division]] to begin the following season with Drogheda United among the four clubs who were relegated from the Premier Division but in this season also Drogheda United entered European Competition for the first time where they were destroyed against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in the [[UEFA Cup]] First Round 14\u20130 on aggregate. They remained in the First Division until the 1988\u201389 season when they went up as First Division Champions. Their joy was short-lived, however, as the following season they were relegated although this time they achieved promotion at the first time of asking. In the next two seasons Drogheda battled bravely against relegation surviving by one point and on goal difference in the respective seasons. However, they were relegated for the third time in the 1993\u201394 season.\n\nDrogheda United were very much becoming a [[yo-yo club]], swapping divisions every season between the 1993\u201394 and 2000\u201301 seasons when in 2000\u201301 they finished a disappointing ninth in the ten-team First Division. In 2002\u201303 they were promoted to the Premier Division under [[Harry McCue]] and were there until the 2016 season, as they got relegated in 2015, coming in twelfth place.\n\n=== 2003\u20132008: Paul Doolin ===\nIn 2003, McCue was sacked as manager of Drogheda United. Paul Doolin took over and upped the standard of training and fitness levels. However, he found that to compete with the big clubs like [[Bohemian F.C.|Bohemians]] and [[Shelbourne F.C.|Shelbourne]] he would need a professional squad. In 2004, he made the squad fully professional and gave part-time players the option to turn professional or leave the club. The change to full-time saw the club's fortunes drastically improve. They won their first [[FAI Cup]] in [[2005 FAI Cup|2005]], beating [[Cork City F.C.|Cork City]] in the final and won back-to-back [[Setanta Cup]]s in [[2006 Setanta Sports Cup|2006]] and [[2007 Setanta Sports Cup|2007]].\n\nThey also qualified for the [[UEFA Cup]] for the 2006\u201307 season thanks to their 2005 FAI Cup success. This time they fared better than in their first foray into Europe as they defeated [[HJK Helsinki]] 4\u20132 on aggregate in the First Qualifying Round and were just eliminated 11\u201310 in an epic penalty shoot-out in the next round against [[IK Start]] of [[Norway]]. They were also in the UEFA Cup Qualifying stages for the 2007\u201308 campaign, losing to [[Helsingborgs IF]] in the second round.\n\nUnited finally won the League of Ireland for the first time in 2007, beating Cork City 2\u20131 at United Park with three games to go. [[Guy Bates]] scored the winning goal for Drogheda that day, shooting himself into Drogs folklore. Drogheda were dominant in the league, only losing three games and winning the title by seven points.\n\nThe league win meant that Drogheda would be playing in the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] Qualifiers for the first time in their history in the 2008\u201309 season. They succeeded in their first qualifier against [[FC Levadia Tallinn|Levadia Tallinn]], beating them 3\u20131 on aggregate. They played the Second Qualifying Round against [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]] which, they ended up losing 4\u20133 on aggregate. In the first a late goal for [[Kiev]] secured a 2\u20131 victory at [[Dalymount Park]]. In the second game, an early Kiev goal after 13 minutes seemed to have finished the tie, but remarkably, on 41 minutes, Drogheda were awarded a penalty. [[Shane Robinson (footballer)|Shane Robinson]] stepped up and slotted home the spot-kick. Drogheda then worked tirelessly trying to get the second goal, but they gave away a penalty on 72 minutes, which was converted. 2\u20131 down, it seemed the tie was over now. Amazingly however, [[Graham Gartland]] scored an 88th-minute goal to make it 2\u20132. [[Adam Hughes (footballer)|Adam Hughes]] got a further chance when he had an open goal, but miskicked the ball and it flew over the bar. Then, [[Shane Robinson (footballer)|Shane Robinson]] hit a shot from a tight angle which hit the post. Despite Drogheda's late rally, they were knocked out by [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]].\n\n=== 2008 (Examinership) ===\n[[File:Hanaphy DUFC Huskie.jpg|thumb|right|200px|alt=Darragh Hanaphy in action for Drogheda United April 2011|Darragh Hanaphy in action for Drogheda United, April 2011]] In October 2008 Drogheda went into [[examinership]], like Cork City, after failing to pay back a \u20ac500,000 loan to the Revenue Commissioners and  \u20ac10,000 rent to [[Bohemian F.C.|Bohemians]] for their use of [[Dalymount Park]] in their [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] Qualifiers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/league-of-ireland/drogs-need-500000-to-avoid-extinction-1559879.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120905235538/http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/league-of-ireland/drogs-need-500000-to-avoid-extinction-1559879.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 September 2012 |work=Irish Independent |title=Drogs need \u20ac500,000 to avoid extinction |date=3 December 2012 }}</ref> Their plans for a new \u20ac35m stadium fell through and in November 2008 they were deduced 10 points. After successfully raising money through various fund raisers arranged by the supporters, the club escaped extinction in January 2009 when a judge ruled in Drogheda's favour to the delight of the teary eyed chairman Vincent Hoey.\n\n=== 2009\u20132011 ===\nIn the 2009 season Drogheda got off to a difficult start. Due to bankruptcy, the club went part-time and lost their entire league-winning squad, and manager, [[Paul Doolin]], who took over [[Cork City F.C.|Cork City]]. Former [[Cork City Football Club|Cork]] and [[Longford Town F.C.|Longford]] boss [[Alan Mathews]] took over.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/soccer/2009/0204/1224240566254.html|title=Mathews appointed Drogheda boss|author=|date=|website=irishtimes.com}}</ref> Mathews had to sign a side of semi-pros and free agents. Drogheda were in the bottom half of the table for the whole season, despite some shock wins. On 10 November 2009 they beat Bray Wanderers 2\u20130 in a relegation play-off.\n\nThe 2010 season was disastrous on and off the pitch. Drogheda started terribly and after a 6\u20130 loss at the hands of [[Sligo Rovers F.C|Sligo Rovers]] on 15 May, Alan Mathews quit his managerial post. The club appointed youth team coach and Drogheda native Darius Kierans as manager even though he had yet to complete his Europa A licence which is an FAI requirement for league managers. After much objection from the FAI, Kierans became Director of Football and the club appointed Paul Lumsden as Interim Manager.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/manager-chaos-may-see-drogs-licence-revoked-2232500.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120802082703/http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/manager-chaos-may-see-drogs-licence-revoked-2232500.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2 August 2012 |work=Irish Independent |title=Manager chaos may see Drogs' licence revoked |date=30 November 2012 }}</ref> Lumsden took the team for only one game before resigning.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.breakingnews.ie/sport/valuable-three-points-for-drogheda-463996.html|title=Valuable three points for Drogheda|author=|date=2 July 2010 |website=breakingnews.ie}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113132806/https://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/2010/0705/267639-dundalk_drogheda/\n|archivedate=13 November 2018 |url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/2010/0705/267639-dundalk_drogheda/ |title=Dundalk 2-1 Drogheda United |accessdate=13 November 2018 |website=[[RTE.ie]] |date=5 July 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> Brian Donnelly was then appointed as the second Interim Manager of the season but he too resigned in September. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drogheda-independent.ie/sport/soccer/donnelly-named-as-drogheda-manager-2258199.html|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120729140146/http://www.drogheda-independent.ie/sport/soccer/donnelly-named-as-drogheda-manager-2258199.html|url-status=dead|title=Donnelly named as Drogheda manager - Soccer, Sport - Drogheda-Indepen\u2026|date=29 July 2012|archivedate=29 July 2012|website=drogheda-independent.ie}}</ref> On 27 September, the club announced the imminent arrival as manager of another former player \u2013 [[Bobby Browne (footballer born 1962)|Bobby Browne]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.droghedaunited.ie/news/2010/september/news_018.php|title=Drogheda United Football Club - Welcome|author=|date=|website=www.droghedaunited.ie|access-date=28 September 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928111600/http://www.droghedaunited.ie/news/2010/september/news_018.php|archive-date=28 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Despite finishing rock-bottom of the table with only four wins and nine draws (a total of 21 points) in 2010 and being relegated, Drogheda United were reprieved after the extinction of [[Sporting Fingal F.C.|Sporting Fingal]] in February 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/2011/0214/premierdivision.html |work=RT\u00c9 News |title=Drogheda back in the Premier Division |date=14 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110215125710/http://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/2011/0214/premierdivision.html |archivedate=15 February 2011 }}</ref>\n\n=== 2011\u20132013: Mick Cooke ===\n\n[[Mick Cooke (football manager)|Mick Cooke]], manager of [[Monaghan United F.C.|Monaghan]] took over as manager on 27 February 2011, becoming the sixth Drogheda manager in nine months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2011/0228/1224291008747.html|title=Drogheda turn to Cooke as Browne leaves the club|author=|date=|website=irishtimes.com}}</ref> Cooke appointed former Drogs goalkeeper, [[Robbie Horgan]] as his assistant, and inherited the players who had been signed by Bobby Browne to play in the First Division so hopes weren't high. After an awful start, Drogheda beat local rivals Dundalk 2\u20131 in Oriel Park. The win turned their season around and despite operating on the lowest playing budget in the league, Drogheda managed to avoid relegation. Shortly after, Cooke put pen to paper on a new three-year deal with the club.\n\nIn 2012, Cooke and Horgan set about building on the foundations of the previous season. Cooke finally had his own team of players and despite having less than a tenth of the budget that the club had in the glory days under Paul Doolin, Drogheda have had their best season by far since then. Between 1 June and 4 August, Drogheda went on an eight-game winning run in the league and cup \u2013 the longest winning run in the club's history. On 23 September 2012, Drogheda won the final of the [[EA Sports Cup]] beating Shamrock Rovers 3\u20131<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/2012/0922/338646-shamrock-rovers-drogheda-united/ | work=RT\u00c9 News | title=Shamrock Rovers 1\u20133 Drogheda United | date=22 September 2012}}</ref> \u2013 their first trophy since 2007. The icing on the cake came on 19 October when Drogheda beat the newly crowned 2012 League Champions Sligo Rovers 2\u20131 at United Park through a first half Alan McNally header and 88th minute Brian Gannon chip to qualify for the Europa League. \n\nIn 2013, Drogheda reached three finals and despite failing to add to their silverware, reflected the club's rise under Cooke. They were beaten 7\u20131 in the Setanta Cup final by [[Shamrock Rovers F.C.|Shamrock Rovers]] and 2\u20130 in the League Cup final by the same opponent. They also reached their first [[2013 FAI Cup Final|FAI Cup final]] since winning the competition in 2005, narrowly losing out on a 3-2 thriller against [[Sligo Rovers F.C.|Sligo Rovers]]. In the Europa League qualifying rounds that season, the club were drawn against Swedish giants [[Malm\u00f6 FF|Malm\u00f6]] and only lost by a single goal over two legs after a battling performance. Despite this success, Mick Cooke left the club by mutual consent at the end of the season.\n\n=== 2015\u2013present ===\nIn November 2015 Drogheda appointed former UCD manager Peter Mahon as manager of the club. John Gill took over as assistant manager with Mark Kinsella ex Irish international remaining part of the coaching staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/league-of-ireland/drogheda-united-announce-pete-mahon-as-new-manager-34188432.html|title=Drogheda United announce Pete Mahon as new manager - Independent.ie|author=|date=|website=independent.ie}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2015 League of Ireland Premier Division|2015]], Drogheda were relegated after finishing bottom of the league. The following season they finished second in the [[2016 League of Ireland First Division|First Division]], achieving promotion through the play-offs, before being relegated again after another 12th-place finish in 2017. In 2018, [[Tim Clancy]] was appointed as manager after the departure of Mahon\n\n== The Claret & Blue Club ==\nIn response to the economic difficulties facing the country, a group of supporters established The Claret & Blue Club in June 2009 with the aim of providing a steady income stream to Drogheda United FC. Supporters who join the Claret & Blue Club donate at least \u20ac5 per week to the club, and in return, they receive a membership card entitling them to discounts of up to 10% in a range of local businesses, including restaurants, tile shops, shoe shops and many more. Each member is also entered in a monthly prize draw, with a top prize every month of a sun holiday courtesy of Panorama Holidays. Other prizes include hotel vouchers, tickets to Irish World Cup qualifier games, betting vouchers etc. Publicity on the Derek Mooney Show on RT\u00c9 Radio one and full-page ads in the Drogheda Independent and Drogheda People resulted in a surge of membership, and after only four weeks of existence, the Claret & Blue Club was in a position to bring in over \u20ac35,000 to the club annually, with membership figures rising daily. It was hoped that the Claret & Blue Club will take full ownership of the club in 2010 and run the club similar to the way [[Shamrock Rovers F.C.|Shamrock Rovers]] is run by the Shamrock Rovers Members Club. However the target of 500 members was not reached and membership levels settled at just over half that target.\n\n=== Share Issue ===\nIn January 2011, a Claret and Blue Club steering committee announced new plans for a share issue. It was hoped that 200 shares would be sold at \u20ac1000 each and that this new revenue would provide stability for 2011\u201312 and allow the club to finally become a supporter-owned community club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.droghedaunited.ie/news/2011/february/news_001.php|title=Drogheda United Football Club - Welcome|author=|date=|website=www.droghedaunited.ie|access-date=15 February 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110705093111/http://www.droghedaunited.ie/news/2011/february/news_001.php|archive-date=5 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> In early 2012 Drogheda United became a member's owned and run club when a new company Drogheda Utd FC Limited was formed consisting of members who paid \u20ac1,000 each into the company.\n\n== Emblem ==\n[[File:Drogheda crest.svg|65px|thumb|right|Drogheda coat of arms.]] The crest of Drogheda United is an adaptation of the [[Drogheda#History#town arms|town arms of Drogheda]], which feature the [[heraldic]] symbols of a [[Star (heraldry)|star]] and [[crescent]] over a shield depicting St. Lawrence's Gate, [[Lion (heraldry)|three lions]] and a ship. The three lions passant \u2013 as Drogheda lay within the [[The Pale|Pale]] and was a besieged garrison town \u2013 and the ship represents the town's port.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://www.ngw.nl/int/ier/d/drogheda.htm|title=Heraldry of the world - Category:Irish municipalities|author=|date=|website=www.ngw.nl}}</ref>\n\nThe club crest focuses on the star and crescent element of the town arms of Drogheda, and are the royal seal of [[John, King of England|King John]], who gave the town its charter.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> The crest is similar to that of [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] in England, given by [[King Richard I of England]]. His own crest was the source of the star and crescent symbols, which he had taken from the [[Byzantine Emperor]]'s standard of Governor [[Isaac Komnenos of Cyprus|Isaac Komnenos]] after capturing [[Cyprus]].\n\nThey share the same club colours as [[Trabzonspor]], in [[Turkey]] \u2013 and in 2011 the two sides became sister clubs. These were given in favor of the [[Ottoman Sultan]] [[Abdulmejid I]]'s great assistance during the [[Irish famine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.droghedaunited.ie/news/2010/september/news_022.php|title=Drogheda United Football Club - Welcome|website=www.droghedaunited.ie|access-date=9 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101004114628/http://www.droghedaunited.ie/news/2010/september/news_022.php|archive-date=4 October 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigsoccer.com/forum/showthread.php?p=21924602|title=Trabzonspor 2010/2011 season {R}|author=|date=|website=bigsoccer.com}}</ref>\n\n==Supporters and rivalries==\n'''Drogs''' is a nickname for supporters of the club. When the name '''Drogs''' started to appear in two newspapers in the late 1990s, The Sun and the Drogheda Leader, the club wrote to the Drogheda Leader Newspaper demanding that the name not be used adding that it was not used in the stadium by the fans. The newspaper argued that it had not invented the name and that the fans in the '''shed''' side of the stadium often sing a song called '''Super Drogs'''. The club considered the name was degrading and was purely a Drogheda Leader nickname not used by the supporters. In recent years the club officially embraced the nickname.\n\nThe most vocal supporters stand on \"the shed side\" of [[United Park]]. Many Drogs attend every home match while a smaller group travel around the country to support the team at away matches. They sing football/Drogheda United chants, wear club colours (claret and blue), wave banners and flags and generally try to help lift the team and demonstrate fervent support. One section of their supporters are known as 'F45U' (Famous 45 [[Ultras]].)\n\nDrogheda United Supporters Club (DUSC) was formed more than two years ago. Its main aim is to promote Drogheda United F.C. throughout the community. The supporters club works hand-in-hand with the football club in various ways including contributing to the match day programme, organising fund raising nights like quizzes and race nights and by organising buses to away matches.<ref>[http://www.droghedaunited.ie/Scripts/SupportersClub.asp Supporters Club] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070823193003/http://www.droghedaunited.ie/Scripts/SupportersClub.asp |date=23 August 2007 }}, ''Drogheda United Official Website'', 2007. Retrieved on 2 August 2007.</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n*'''[[League of Ireland Premier Division]]: 1'''\n** [[2007 League of Ireland Premier Division|2007]]\n** Runner-up [[2012 League of Ireland Premier Division|2012]]\n*'''