{"title_page": "\u015a\u0101riputra", "text_new": "{{short description|Main disciple of Gautama Buddha}}\n{{Infobox religious biography\n|background = #FFD068\n|name = \u015a\u0101riputra\n|image =Sariputta-statue.jpg\n|caption =Statue of \u015a\u0101riputra, depicting his \"golden complexion\". \n|birth_name = Upati\u1e63ya (Pali: ''Upatissa'')\n|alias = \n|dharma name = \u015a\u0101riputra\n|birth_place = N\u0101laka or Upati\u1e63ya Village, [[Rajgir]], [[Magadha]]\n|death_place = N\u0101laka or Upati\u1e63ya Village, [[Rajgir]], [[Magadha]]\n|religion = [[Buddhism]]\n|school = \n|lineage = \n|title = First chief disciple (Pa\u1e6dhamas\u0101vaka), right hand side chief disciple (Dakkhinas\u0101vaka), foremost of the wise \n|location = \n|education = \n|teacher = [[Gautama Buddha]]\n|reincarnation of = \n|predecessor = \n|successor =  \n|students = \n|parents = Va\u1e47ganta or Tisya (father), S\u0101ri (mother)\n|spouse = \n|partner = \n|children = \n|website = \n}}\n{{ Infobox Buddhist term\n| title = \u015a\u0101riputra\n| en = \n| pi = S\u0101riputta\n| sa = \u0936\u093e\u0930\u093f\u092a\u0941\u0924\u094d\u0930<br>\u015a\u0101riputra<br/>\n| bn = \n| my  = \u101b\u103e\u1004\u103a\u101e\u102c\u101b\u102d\u1015\u102f\u1010\u1039\u1010\u101b\u102c<br>(Shin S\u0101riputtar\u0101)\n| my-Latn = \n| zh = \u820e\u5229\u5f17\n| zh-Latn = Sh\u00e8l\u00ecf\u00fa)<br>\u820e\u5229\u5b50<br>([[Pinyin]]: Sh\u00e8l\u00eczi\n| ja = {{ruby-ja|\u820e\u5229\u5f17|\u3057\u3083\u308a\u307b\u3064}}\n| ja-Latn = Sharihotsu)<br>{{ruby-ja|\u820e\u5229\u5b50|\u3057\u3083\u308a\u3057}}<br>([[romaji]]: Sharishi\n| km = \u179f\u17b6\u179a\u17b8\u1794\u17bb\u178f\u17d2\u179a<br>([[UNGEGN]]: sareib\u014ft)\n| ko = \uc0ac\ub9ac\ubd88\n| ko-Latn = Saripul\n| mnw = \n| mnw-Latn = \n| shn = \n| shn-Latn = \n| si =\u0dc3\u0dcf\u0dbb\u0dd2\u0db4\u0dd4\u0dad\u0dca\u0dad\n| si-Latn = \n| ta = \n| th = \u0e2a\u0e32\u0e23\u0e35\u0e1a\u0e38\u0e15\u0e23<br>({{rtgs|Saribut}})\n| bo = <big><big>\u0f64\u0f71\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f72\u0f60\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f74\u0f0b</big></big>\n| bo-Latn = [[Wylie transliteration|Wylie]]: shA ri'i bu)<br>([[THL Simplified Phonetic Transcription|THL]]: sha ri bu\n| vi = X\u00e1 L\u1ee3i Ph\u1ea5t<br>X\u00e1 L\u1ee3i T\u1eed\n| id = \n}}\n{{Buddhism}}\n'''\u015a\u0101riputra''' ({{lang-sa|\u0936\u093e\u0930\u093f\u092a\u0941\u0924\u094d\u0930|\u015a\u0101riputra}}; Tibetan: \u0f64\u0f71\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f72\u0f60\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f74\u0f0b, [[Pali]]: ''S\u0101riputta'') (lit. \"the son of \u015a\u0101ri\"); born '''Upati\u1e63ya''' (Pali: ''Upatissa''); was one of the top disciples of [[Gautama Buddha|the Buddha]]. He is considered the first of the Buddha's two chief disciples, together with [[Maudgaly\u0101yana ]] (Pali: ''Moggall\u0101na''). \u015a\u0101riputra had a key leadership role in the ministry of the Buddha and is considered in many Buddhist schools to have been important in the development of the Buddhist ''[[Abhidharma]]''. He appears in several [[Mahayana sutras]], and in some sutras, is used as a counterpoint to represent the [[Hinayana]] school of Buddhism.  \n\nBuddhist texts relate that \u015a\u0101riputra and Maudgaly\u0101yana were childhood friends who became spiritual wanderers in their youth. After having searched for spiritual truth for a while, they came into contact with the teachings of the Buddha and ordained as monks under him, after which the Buddha declared the friends his two chief disciples. \u015a\u0101riputra was said to have attained enlightenment as an [[arahant|arhat]] two weeks after ordaining. As chief disciple \u015a\u0101riputra assumed a leadership role in the [[Sangha]], doing tasks like looking after monks, giving them objects of meditation, and clarifying points of doctrine. He was the first disciple the Buddha allowed to ordain other monks. \u015a\u0101riputra died shortly before the Buddha in his hometown and was cremated. According to Buddhist texts, his relics were then enshrined at [[Jetavana]] Monastery. Archaeological findings from the 1800s suggest his relics may have been redistributed across the Indian subcontinent by subsequent kings.  \n\n\u015a\u0101riputra is regarded as an important and wise disciple of the Buddha, particularly in [[Theravada]] Buddhism where he is given a status close to a second Buddha. In [[Buddhist art]], he is often depicted alongside the Buddha, usually to his right. \u015a\u0101riputra was known for his strict adherence to the Buddhist [[Vinaya|monastic rules]], as well as for his wisdom and teaching ability, giving him the title \"General of the Dharma\" (Sanskrit: ''Dharmasenapati''; Pali: ''Dhammasen\u0101pati''). \u015a\u0101riputra is considered the disciple of the Buddha who was foremost in [[Praj\u00f1\u0101 (Buddhism)|wisdom]]. His female counterpart was [[Khema|K\u1e63em\u0101]].{{sfn|Krey|2010|p=19}} \n\n== Background ==\nAccording to [[Buddhist texts]], when a fully enlightened [[Buddha (title)|Buddha]] arrives in the world, he always has a set of chief disciples.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=31-32}} For the current Buddha, [[Gautama Buddha|Gautama]], his chief male disciples were \u015a\u0101riputra and [[Maudgalyayana|Maudgaly\u0101yana]], while his chief female disciples were [[Khema|K\u1e63em\u0101]] and [[Utpalavar\u1e47\u0101]].{{sfn|Mahathera|1998|p=235}}{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=376-377}} According to the [[Buddhava\u1e43sa]], all Buddhas of the past followed this pattern of selecting two chief male disciples and two chief female disciples.{{sfn|Shaw|2013|p=455}} German Buddhist scholar monk [[Nyanaponika Thera]] states that the reason Buddhas always select two chief disciples is to balance responsibilities according to each disciple's specific skills.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=67}}\n\nAccording to the [[P\u0101li Canon|Pali Canon]], in the distant past \u015a\u0101riputra was born a wealthy [[Brahmin#In Buddhist and Jaina texts|Brahmin]] named Sarada who gave away his wealth to become an ascetic who developed a large following. At that time, Sarada and his followers were visited by the past Buddha, [[Anomadassi Buddha|Anomadass\u012b,]] and were given a sermon given by Anomadass\u012b Buddha's chief disciples. Upon hearing the sermon from Anomadass\u012b Buddha's first chief disciple, Nisabha, Sarada became inspired and [[Adhi\u1e6d\u1e6dh\u0101na|resolved]] to become the first chief disciple of a future Buddha. He then made this wish in front of Anomadass\u012b Buddha, who declared that his aspiration will come true. Upon hearing the prediction, Sarada went to his close friend Sirivaddhana and asked him to resolve to become the second chief disciple of the same Buddha. Sirivaddhana then made a large offering to Anomadass\u012b Buddha and his following and made the wish as suggested.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=58-61}} The two friends then spent the rest of their lives and several future lives doing good deeds.{{sfn|Malalasekera|2007|p=542}} According to Buddhist legend, the wish came true in the time of Gautama Buddha with Sarada being reborn as \u015a\u0101riputra and Sirivaddhana being reborn as Maudgaly\u0101yana.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=58-61}}{{sfn|Malalasekera|2007|p=542}}\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Early life ===\nBuddhist texts describe that \u015a\u0101riputra was born with the birth name Upati\u1e63ya ([[Pali]]: ''Upatissa'') to a  wealthy [[Brahmin#In Buddhist and Jaina texts|Brahmin]] family in a village near [[R\u0101jagaha]] in the ancient Indian kingdom of [[Magadha]].{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=521}}{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=410}}{{sfn|Sayadaw|1990}} He is described as having had a \"golden complexion\".{{sfn|Shaw|2013|p=458}}{{sfn|Shaw|2006|p=36}}\n\nTexts from the [[Mulasarvastivada]] tradition state he was named after his father, while the [[Pali]] commentaries of the [[Theravada]] tradition state he was named after his birth village.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=410}}{{refn|Some Pali texts contradict this however and state his birth village as N\u0101laka,{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=410}} although this may be an alternative name for Upatissa.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=521}}|group=note}} Upati\u1e63ya had six siblings; three brothers named Upasena, Cunda and Revata, and three sisters named C\u0101la, Upac\u0101l\u0101 and S\u012bsupac\u0101l\u0101. Each of his siblings would grow up to become [[arhat]] disciples of the Buddha.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=411}} According to the Pali tradition, Upati\u1e63ya's father was named Vangunta, while according to Mulasarvastivada tradition his father was named Ti\u1e63ya ([[Pali]]: ''Tissa'').{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=410}} Upati\u1e63ya's mother was named \u015a\u0101r\u012b (alternatively called R\u016bpa\u015b\u0101r\u012b, \u015a\u0101rika, or \u015a\u0101radvat\u012b), for which he later became known as \u015a\u0101riputra (son of \u015a\u0101ri) and sometimes \u015a\u0101radvat\u012bputra (son of \u015a\u0101radvat\u012b).<ref>{{cite web |title=Sharadvatiputra, aka: \u015a\u0101radvat\u012bputra |url=https://www.wisdomlib.org/definition/sharadvatiputra |website=Wisdom Library |accessdate=2019-12-24 |date=2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225044031/https://www.wisdomlib.org/definition/sharadvatiputra |archive-date=2019-12-25 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{sfn|Buswell|Lopez|2013|p=1902}}[[File:Nalanda Sariputta Stupa.jpg|left|thumb|A stupa dedicated to \u015a\u0101riputra at the ancient [[Nalanda]] monastery.  Nyanaponika Thera states that Nalanda was probably close to where \u015a\u0101riputra was born and died.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=521}}|alt=]]\n\nUpati\u1e63ya was born the same day as Kolita (who would later be known as [[Maudgaly\u0101yana]]), a boy from a neighboring village whose family had been friends with Upati\u1e63ya's family for seven generations, and became friends with him as a child.{{sfn|Thakur|1996|p=66}}{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=49}}{{sfn|Daulton|1999|p=102}} Upati\u1e63ya and Kolita both became masters of the [[Vedas]] through their education and each developed a large following of Brahmin youths. One day the realization that life is impermanent overtook the two friends during a festival in R\u0101jagaha and they developed a [[Samvega|sense of spiritual urgency]].{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=411}}{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=49-50}}\n\nRealizing the pointlessness of the impermanent material world, the two friends set out as ascetics to search for an end to rebirth. In Mulasarvastivada texts, the two friends visited all [[Six heretical teachers|six major teachers]] of India at the time before realizing none of them had the right path.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=411}} According to Pali texts, the two friends and their following of Brahmin youths became students under only one of the teachers, the ascetic ''[[Sa\u00f1jaya Vairatiputra]]'' (Pali: ''Sa\u00f1jaya Bela\u1e6d\u1e6dhaputta''), who was staying nearby.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=411}}{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=4-5}} Pali texts describe Sa\u00f1jaya as a teacher in the [[Aj\u00f1ana|Indian Sceptic]] tradition, with Upati\u1e63ya and Kolita eventually becoming dissatisfied with his teachings and leaving.{{sfn|Harvey|2013|p=14}}{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=411}} In [[M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101da]] texts, the [[Chinese Buddhist Canon]] and in [[Tibetan canon|Tibetan accounts]], however, he is depicted as a wise teacher with [[Abhinna|meditative vision]] who becomes ill and dies. In some accounts, he predicts the coming of the Buddha through his visions.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lamotte|first=E.|title=La l\u00e9gende du Buddha|author-link=\u00c9tienne Lamotte|language=fr|trans-title=The legend of the Buddha|journal=Revue de l'histoire des religions|volume=134|issue=1\u20133|year=1947|doi=10.3406/rhr.1947.5599|pages=65\u20136}}</ref>{{sfn|Migot|1954|pp=430\u20132, 440, 448}} After being unable to find what they were looking for, the two friends went their separate ways but made a pact that if one was to find the path to the [[Nirvana (Buddhism)|deathless]], they would tell the other.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=51}}{{sfn|Buswell|Lopez|2013|p=1903}}{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=411}}\n\n=== Meeting the Buddha ===\n[[File:Sariputra and Maudgalyayana become disciples of Buddha Roundel 31 buddha ivory tusk.jpg|thumb|Ivory relief depicting \u015a\u0101riputra and Maudgaly\u0101yana becoming disciples of the Buddha]]\nAfter leaving Sa\u00f1jaya, Upati\u1e63ya encountered the monk [[Assaji|A\u015bvajit]] (''{{lang-pi|Assaji}}''), one of the Buddha's first five arhat disciples. Upatissa noticed how serene the monk appeared and approached him to ask for a teaching.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=51-53}} A\u015bvajit said he was still newly ordained but will teach what he can, and proceeded to teach the famous [[Ye Dharma Hetu]] stanza:{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=53}}\n\n{{cquote|Of all those things that from a cause arise,\n\n[[Tathagata]] the cause thereof has told;\n\nAnd how they cease to be, that too he tells,\n\nThis is the doctrine of the Great Recluse.\n| author = Translated by [[Nyanaponika Thera]]\n}}\n\nThis stanza has become particularly famous in the Buddhist world, having been inscribed onto many Buddhist statues.{{sfn|Carus|1905|p=180}} According to philosopher [[Paul Carus]], the stanza breaks away from the idea of divine intervention prevalent in ancient [[Brahmanism]] at the time and instead teaches that the origin and end of all things depends on its causation.{{sfn|Carus|1905|p=180-181}}\n\nFollowing the teaching, Upati\u1e63ya attained [[Sot\u0101panna|sotapanna]], the first [[Four stages of enlightenment|stage of enlightenment]].{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=53}} Upati\u1e63ya then went to Kolita to tell him about the incident and, after reciting the stanza for him, Kolita also attained sotapanna.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=54}}{{sfn|Buswell|Lopez|2013|p=1903}}{{refn|In one version of the Chinese Buddhist canon, \u015a\u0101riputra first went to the Buddha alone after being converted by A\u015bvajit, and then asked the Buddha for permission to go find his friend.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=450}}|group=note}} The two friends, along with a large chunk of Sa\u00f1jaya's disciples, then [[Upasampada|ordained as monks]] under the Buddha, with everybody in the group becoming arhats that day except for Upati\u1e63ya and Kolita.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=55-56}}{{sfn|Buswell|Lopez|2013|p=1903}}{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=451}} Nyanaponika Thera states that the friends required longer preparatory periods before enlightening in order to fulfill their roles as chief disciples.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=56}} Several texts describe the ordination with miraculous elements, such as the disciples' clothes suddenly being replaced with Buddhist robes and their hair falling out on its own.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=451}} After ordaining, Upati\u1e63ya started being called \u015a\u0101riputra (Pali: ''S\u0101riputta''), and Kolita started being called [[Maudgaly\u0101yana]] (Pali: ''Moggall\u0101na'').{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=56}}\n\nAfter \u015a\u0101riputra and Maudgaly\u0101yana ordained, the Buddha declared them his two chief disciples (Pali: ''aggasavaka''), following the tradition of appointing a pair of chief disciples as the past Buddhas did, according to Buddhist belief.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=31-32,57}}{{sfn|Daulton|1999|p=104}}{{sfn|Buswell|Lopez|2013|p=1903}} Since they were newly ordained some of the monks in the assembly felt offended, but the Buddha explained that he gave them the roles because they had made the [[Adhi\u1e6d\u1e6dh\u0101na|resolve]] to become the chief disciples many lifetimes ago.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=57-58}}{{sfn|Malalasekera|2007|p=542}} Maudgaly\u0101yana attained arhatship seven days after ordaining following intense meditation training. \u015a\u0101riputra attained arhatship two weeks after ordaining while fanning the Buddha as the Buddha was delivering the ''Vedan\u0101pariggaha Sutta'' to a wandering ascetic.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=56-57}}{{sfn|Buswell|Lopez|2013|p=1903}} Pali texts state that the ascetic was \u015a\u0101riputra's nephew but Chinese, Tibetan and Sanskrit texts state he was \u015a\u0101riputra's uncle.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=452}} According to commentaries such as the [[Atthakatha]], \u015a\u0101riputra took longer to achieve enlightenment than Maudgaly\u0101yana because his knowledge had to be more thorough as first chief disciple, and thus required more preparation time.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=452}}\n=== Chief disciple ===\n[[File:Bodh Gaya - Buddha Statue - Sariputta (9224957409).jpg|thumb|A statue of \u015a\u0101riputra at [[Bodh Gaya]].]]\n\u015a\u0101riputra is considered to have been the Buddha's first chief disciple, foremost in [[Pa\u00f1\u00f1\u0101|wisdom]]. He shared the title of chief disciple with Maudgaly\u0101yana, together described in the ''Mah\u0101pad\u0101na Sutta,'' as \"the chief pair of disciples, the excellent pair\" (Pali: s\u0101vakayuga\u1e41 agga\u1e41 bhaddayuga\u1e41).{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=65}} In the [[Mahavagga]], the Buddha declared his two chief disciples as being foremost in wisdom and foremost in [[iddhi|psychic powers]], referencing \u015a\u0101riputra and Maudgaly\u0101yana respectively.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=416}} Texts describe that none of the Buddha's other disciples could answer questions that Maudgaly\u0101yana was able to answer while Maudgaly\u0101yana was unable to answer questions \u015a\u0101riputra was able to answer.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=413}} As the first chief disciple, \u015a\u0101riputra's role was the systematization and analysis of the Buddha's teachings.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=67}} The Buddhist canon often shows \u015a\u0101riputra asking the Buddha questions and entreating the Buddha to teach, as well as himself clarifying points and questioning disciples, in some cases seemingly to test the knowledge of fellow disciples.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=407,462-463}}{{sfn|Krey|2010|p=23}} The Buddha would often suggest a topic and have \u015a\u0101riputra elaborate and deliver a sermon on it.{{sfn|Malalasekera|1937|p=}} In two discourses recorded in the [[Tripi\u1e6daka|Tripitaka]], the ''Dasuttara Sutta'' and the ''Sa\u1e45g\u012bti Sutta'', the Buddha declared he needed to rest his back, and had \u015a\u0101riputra teach in his place while the Buddha listened in the audience.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=413}}{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=408,467}}{{sfn|Buswell|Lopez|2013|p=1903}} His ability to teach the [[Dharma (Buddhism)|Dharma]] earned him the title of \"General of the Dharma\" (Sanskrit: ''Dharmasenapati'').{{sfn|Malalasekera|1937|p=}}{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=413}}{{sfn|Buswell|Lopez|2013|p=1903}} Buddhist texts indicate that \u015a\u0101riputra still had some flaws, however. In the ''Catuma Sutta'', when a group of young monks made noise and were ordered by the Buddha to leave, the Buddha reprimanded \u015a\u0101riputra for not concluding that it was the chief disciples' responsibility to look after the monks, something Maudgaly\u0101yana was able to conclude to.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=69-70}} On another occasion the Buddha reprimanded \u015a\u0101riputra for teaching the dying brahmin, Dhana\u00f1jani, in a way that led him to rebirth in the Brahma realm rather than teaching in a way that led to enlightenment.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=74-75}}{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=413}}\n\nBuddhist texts portray \u015a\u0101riputra as someone who took an active role in debating and converting [[Tirthika|heretics]], considered to have been one of his great prerogatives.{{sfn|Ray|1994|p=134}} In the Mulasarvastivada tradition, when the [[six heretical teachers]] of the time challenged the Buddhists to a contest, the Buddha had \u015a\u0101riputra contend against them. Mulasarvastivada texts state that \u015a\u0101riputra used psychic powers to create a huge storm and transform himself into various forms, subduing the rival teachers and converting the residents of Savatthi.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=413-414}} When the monk [[Devadatta]] created a [[schism]] in the Buddha's monastic community and led some of the Buddha's disciples away, \u015a\u0101riputra played a key role in restoring the community. According to texts, upon hearing about the schism, \u015a\u0101riputra and Maudgaly\u0101yana pretended to join Devadatta's community. After the chief disciples joined, Devadatta claimed to have had a backache and had \u015a\u0101riputra preach in his place, but Devadatta fell asleep and \u015a\u0101riputra and Maudgaly\u0101yana used the opportunity to get the following to return to the Buddha.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=414}}{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=471}}\nAs chief disciple, \u015a\u0101riputra assumed a leadership role in the Buddha's monastic community, or [[Sangha]]. Buddhist texts describe that \u015a\u0101riputra routinely took charge of monastic affairs usually handled by the Buddha himself, such as attending to sick monks or visiting lay followers before their deaths.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=413}} In one instance, when a group of monks planned to travel elsewhere, the Buddha told them to ask \u015a\u0101riputra for permission first.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=413}} \u015a\u0101riputra was the first disciple of the Buddha who was asked to ordain monks in his place, with the Buddha giving him the [[Upasampad\u0101|ordination]] procedure. He was also entrusted to ordain the Buddha's son [[Rahula]].{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=471}} When \u015a\u0101riputra trained pupils, he gave them material and spiritual help, and assigned them an object of meditation.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=68-69}} In the ''Saccavibhanga Sutta'', the Buddha compared \u015a\u0101riputra to a mother who gives birth to a child while comparing Maudgaly\u0101yana to a nurse who raises a child. \u015a\u0101riputra would train students to [[sotapanna]], the first stage of enlightenment, and Maudgaly\u0101yana would train students to [[arhatship]], the highest stage of enlightenment.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=68-69}}{{sfn|Malalasekera|1937|p=}}{{refn|American scholar monk [[Thanissaro Bhikkhu]] notes that it may seem strange \u015a\u0101riputra had what appears to have been a lower job than Maudgaly\u0101yana, but states it is actually harder to train an unenlightened person to become a ''sotapanna'' than to train a ''sotapanna'' to become an ''arhat''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bhikkhu |first1=Thanissaro |title=Saccavibhanga Sutta: An Analysis of the Truths |url=https://www.accesstoinsight.org/tipitaka/mn/mn.141.than.html#fnt-1 |website=www.accesstoinsight.org |publisher=Access to Insight |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>|group=note}} However, Nyanaponika Thera notes that there are several individual cases where \u015a\u0101riputra guided monks to the higher stages of enlightenment as well.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=69}}[[File:Sariputta from Myanmar, 19th century, lacquered and gilded wood with glass, HAA.JPG|thumb|Gilded statue of \u015a\u0101riputra from Burma.|alt=|left]]\n\nBuddhist texts generally credit the establishment of the [[Vinaya|monastic rules]] to \u015a\u0101riputra, with \u015a\u0101riputra being the one to ask the Buddha to create the rules. When \u015a\u0101riputra asked the Buddha, he said he would lay them down at the right time.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=413}} \u015a\u0101riputra was known for his conscientiousness and meticulous adherence to monastic rules. In one story, \u015a\u0101riputra became ill with an ailment that could be treated with garlic, but refused it because the Buddha had previously laid down a rule forbidding monks to eat garlic, with \u015a\u0101riputra only taking it after the Buddha rescinded the rule.{{sfn|Malalasekera|1937|p=}}{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=413}} In another story, \u015a\u0101riputra found that meal cakes tended to make him greedy and then made a vow to abstain from them.{{sfn|Malalasekera|1937|p=}} A Buddhist commentary describes that one time when the other monks had left to collect alms, \u015a\u0101riputra meticulously cleaned and organized the monastery to keep heretics from criticizing the disciples.{{sfn|Malalasekera|1937|p=}} Several Buddhists text relate that \u015a\u0101riputra was reborn as a snake in a previous life and that this was the reason for some of his stubbornness. In a [[Mah\u0101s\u0101\u1e43ghika]] text the Buddha punished \u015a\u0101riputra by making him stand in the sun for failing to prevent some monks from making incorrect remarks. When the other monks later asked the Buddha to stop the punishment, the Buddha said that \u015a\u0101riputra's mind to receive the punishment could not be changed just as he was unwilling to change his mind when he was a snake. In a [[Mah\u012b\u015b\u0101saka]] text, \u015a\u0101riputra refused to take [[myrobalan]], even when prescribed as medicine, after another monk suspected him of sneaking delicious food, the Buddha likewise references \u015a\u0101riputra's life as a snake to explain his stubbornness.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=415-416}}\n\nAlthough Maudgaly\u0101yana is described as having been foremost in psychic powers, Buddhist texts state that \u015a\u0101riputra also exhibited such powers himself. In various texts, \u015a\u0101riputra is reported to have exhibited several psychic abilities such as levitation and the ability to visit other realms of existence, as well as abilities common among arhats such as recalling past lives and clairvoyance.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=506}} In one story, a [[yaksha]], or spirit, hit \u015a\u0101riputra in the head while he was meditating. When Maudgaly\u0101yana saw the incident and came to ask \u015a\u0101riputra if he was okay, \u015a\u0101riputra stated he didn't even notice the blow and suffered only a minor headache.{{sfn|Malalasekera|1937|p=}} Maudgaly\u0101yana then praised \u015a\u0101riputra for his psychic abilities by being able to sustain a blow with little notice, described in the [[Patisambhidamagga]] text as an example of \u201cthe power of intervention by concentration\u201d (Pali: ''sam\u0101dhivipph\u0101ra-iddhi'').{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=91-92}} In Mulasarvastivada texts, \u015a\u0101riputra and Maudgaly\u0101yana descended do hell to give [[Devadatta]] the prophecy that he will become a [[pratyekabuddha]] in the future.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=412}} During the visit, it is said that Maudgaly\u0101yana attempted to relieve the suffering of those in hell by creating rain but the rain dispersed. After \u015a\u0101riputra saw this, he created a rain that did relieve the suffering of those in hell, using a wisdom based meditation.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=507-508}} In another Mulasarvastivada text, the Buddha sent Maudgaly\u0101yana to retrieve \u015a\u0101riputra, who was doing sewing work. When \u015a\u0101riputra stated he would go after his sewing work was complete, Maudgaly\u0101yana attempted to force him to come by using his psychic powers to shake the ground but \u015a\u0101riputra was unaffected. When \u015a\u0101riputra told him to return first, Maudgaly\u0101yana went back to the Buddha and found that \u015a\u0101riputra had already arrived.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=412}} When Maudgaly\u0101yana saw this, he stated that the power of psychic abilities was no match for the power of wisdom.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=508}}\n=== Abhidharma ===\n{{Main|Abhidharma}}\n[[File:Buddha preaching Abhidhamma in Tavatimsa.jpg|thumb|According to Theravada tradition, the Buddha taught the ''Abhidharma'' in [[Tavatimsa]] heaven and returned to earth daily to give \u015a\u0101riputra a summary.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=416}}|alt=]]\n\u015a\u0101riputra is said to have played a key role in the development of the ''[[Abhidharma]]'' texts of the Buddhist [[Tripi\u1e6daka|Tripitaka]]. Buddhist scholar monks [[Rewata Dhamma]] and [[Bhikkhu Bodhi]] describe the ''Abhidharma'' as \"an abstract and highly technical systemization of the doctrine\".{{sfn|Bodhi|Dhamma|1993|p=2}} According to [[Theravada]] tradition, the ''Abhidharma'', or \"Higher Dharma\", is said to have been preached by the Buddha to [[Deva (Buddhism)|devas]] while he was spending the rainy season in [[Tavatimsa]] Heaven. It is said that the Buddha returned to earth daily to give a summary to \u015a\u0101riputra, who classified and reordered the teachings and relayed it to his disciples, in what would become the [[Abhidhamma Pi\u1e6daka|''Abhidharma Pitaka'']].{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=416}} Various sets of the ''[[Sarvastivada]]'' school of Buddhism, however, attribute each of the seven books{{refn|Some Buddhist schools classify the ''Abhidharma'' into six or eight parts, rather than seven.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=521}}|group=note}} of the ''Abhidharma'' to different authors, with \u015a\u0101riputra being attributed as the author of just the ''[[Sangitiparyaya]]'' in the Chinese ''Sarvastivada'' tradition and as the author of the ''[[Dharmaskandha]]'' in the Sanskrit and Tibetan ''Sarvastivada'' traditions.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=520}} In the ''Vatsiputriya'' tradition, a subset of the ''Sarvastivada'' school, \u015a\u0101riputra is said to have transmitted the ''Abhidharma'' to Rahula, who later transmitted it to the school's founder, Vatsiputra.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=416}} As the author of the Abhidharma in Buddhist tradition, \u015a\u0101riputra is considered to be the patron saint of the Abhidharmists.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=408}}\nFrench religion writer [[Andr\u00e9 Migot]], argues that the ''Abhidharma'' was formulated no earlier than the time of Emperor [[Asoka]], and thus cannot really be attributed to the historic \u015a\u0101riputra, at least not the version known by modern scholars.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=523}} English historian [[Edward J. Thomas]] dates the development of the ''Abhidharma'' as being sometime between the third century BCE and the first century CE.{{sfn|Thomas|1953|p=158}} However, Migot states that a simpler version of the ''Abhidharma'' likely existed in early Buddhism, before it evolved and was written down in its current form.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=524}} Migot points to the mention of the \"''Matrka\" Pitaka'' in [[Cullavagga]] texts as the precursor to the ''Abhidharma Pitaka''. Migot argues that the ''Matrka Pitaka'', recited by [[Mahakasyapa]] at the [[First Buddhist Council]] according to ''[[Ashokavadana]]'' texts, likely began as a condensed version of Buddhist doctrine that developed overtime with metaphysical aspects to become the ''Abhidharma''.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=524-524,537-540}} Thomas also states that the ''Abhidharma'' had earlier roots and was developed based on existing material, likely a method of discussing the principles of the Buddha's teachings. According to Thomas, different Buddhist schools compiled their own ''Abhidharma'' works separately, but based it on common existing material.{{sfn|Thomas|1953|p=159-160}}[[File:032 Passing of Sariputta (35252914515).jpg|thumb|Painting depicting the death of \u015a\u0101riputra at the [[Bangkok National Museum]].|240x240px]]\n\n=== Death ===\nBuddhist texts all state that \u015a\u0101riputra died shortly before the Buddha, with texts generally indicating he died in his hometown.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=414}}{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=473-474}} According to P\u0101li commentaries, \u015a\u0101riputra arose from meditation one day and realized through his meditative insight that the chief disciples were supposed to achieve [[parinirvana]] before the Buddha, and that he had seven more days to live.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=106-107}}{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=414}} \u015a\u0101riputra then traveled to his hometown to teach his mother, who was yet to be converted to Buddhism. After he successfully converted his mother, \u015a\u0101riputra died peacefully on the full moon day of [[Kartik (month)|Kartika]] a few months before the Buddha.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=414}} According to Mulasarvastivada texts, however, it is said that \u015a\u0101riputra achieved ''paranirvana'' voluntarily because he didn't want to witness the Buddha's death, in some accounts he was also motivated by Maudgaly\u0101yana intending to achieve ''paranirvana'' after being beaten and mortally injured by a rival religious group.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=414}}{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=475}} In the [[Sarv\u0101stiv\u0101da]] account of the story, \u015a\u0101riputra and Maudgaly\u0101yana both achieve ''paranirvana'' voluntarily on the same day, not wanting to witness the Buddha's death.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=476}}\n\nA funeral was held for \u015a\u0101riputra in the city of [[Rajgir]] where his remains were cremated. His relics were then brought by \u015a\u0101riputra's assistant, Cunda, to the Buddha in [[\u015ar\u0101vast\u012b]].{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=414-415}} In the ''Anupada Sutta'', the Buddha gave a eulogy of \u015a\u0101riputra, praising his intellect and virtue.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=484}}{{sfn|Malalasekera|1937|p=}} According to a [[Dighanikaya]] commentary, the Buddha enshrined \u015a\u0101riputra's relics in a [[cetiya]] at [[Jetavana]]. In Mulasarvastivada texts, the relics were given to the lay disciple, [[Anathapindika]], and it is him who builds a [[stupa]] and enshrines the relics at Jetavana.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=414-415}}{{refn|This version conflicts with some texts that state that Anathapindika died first.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=415}}|group=note}}\n\n==In Mahayana Sutras==\n[[File:Manjusri Debates Vimalakirti Dunhuang Mogao Caves.jpeg|thumb|A Chinese painting depicting the events of the ''Vimalak\u012brti'' sutra.]]\n\u015a\u0101riputra appears in several [[Mahayana Sutras]], often asking the Buddha to teach or engaging in the dialogue himself.{{sfn|Lopez|1988|p=51}}\nWhile depictions of \u015a\u0101riputra in the [[P\u0101li Canon]] generally portray him as a wise and powerful arhat, second only to the Buddha, [[Mahayana]] texts give him a wider range of depictions. Some Mahayana sutras portray him as great Buddhist disciple while others portray him as a counterpoint with insufficient understanding of Mahayana doctrine, representative of the [[Hinayana]] tradition.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=416-417}}{{sfn|Irons|2007|p=428}}{{sfn|Buswell|Lopez|2013|p=1904}} Buddhist studies scholar [[Donald S. Lopez Jr.]] describes the latter as \"intentional irony\" aimed at depicting how profound Mahayana doctrine is by showing that even the wisest \"Hinayana\" disciple had difficulty understanding it.{{sfn|Lopez|1988|p=51}} Migot states that it is significant that \u015a\u0101riputra has a continuity in Mahayana texts, as most of the Buddha's great disciples are usually absent from Mahayana literature.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=537}} Migot credits the importance of \u015a\u0101riputra in the early ''Vatsiputriya'' Buddhist school with why \u015a\u0101riputra often appeared in Mahayana texts.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=538}}\n\nIn the ''[[Vimalakirti Sutra|Vimalak\u012brti S\u016btra]]'', \u015a\u0101riputra is depicted as being unable to grasp [[Mahayana]] doctrines such as [[Nondualism|non-duality]] and [[Emptiness (Buddhism)|emptiness]].{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=416-417}} In the sutra, a goddess listening to [[Vimalakirti|Vimalak\u012brti]] scatters flowers which fall onto \u015a\u0101riputra's robes.{{sfn|Berger|1994|p=350-352}} Not wanting to break the monastic rules, which forbid decorating oneself with flowers, he tries to remove them but is unable to.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=416-417}} The goddess then accuses \u015a\u0101riputra of being attached to the duality of what is proper and improper.{{sfn|Berger|1994|p=350-352}}{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=416-417}} Later in the sutra, \u015a\u0101riputra asks that if the goddess is so spiritually advanced, why doesn't she transform out of her female state, indicative of cultural sexism.{{sfn|Berger|1994|p=350-352}} The goddess responds by using her powers to switch bodies with \u015a\u0101riputra to demonstrate that male and female is just an illusion because, according to Mahayana doctrine, all things are empty and so male and female don't really exist.{{sfn|Berger|1994|p=350-352}}{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=416-417}}\n\nIn the ''Astasahasrika Prajnaparamita Sutra'', \u015a\u0101riputra is portrayed as being unable to understand the ultimate meaning of ''[[prajnaparamita]]'' and instead must be instructed by the disciple [[Subh\u016bti]].{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=416-417}} According to Buddhist scholar [[Edward Conze]], the sutra depicts \u015a\u0101riputra as being preoccupied with dualities, making him unable to grasp the true meaning of ''prajnaparamita''.{{sfn|Conze|1983|p=5}} In the ''[[Mahaprajnaparamita Sutra]]'', \u015a\u0101riputra is one of the principal interlocutors, asking questions and being instructed.{{sfn|Conze|1975|p=17,25,28,29}} Conze states that \u015a\u0101riputra has to be instructed in this sutra because, despite his great wisdom, ''prajnaparamita'' doctrine was too advanced for his comprehension.{{sfn|Conze|1975|p=56}} The ''[[Da zhidu lun]]'' commentary to the sutra describes \u015a\u0101riputra as someone who pursued the [[bodhisattva]] path in a past life but gave up and turned to the ''[[\u015ar\u0101vaka]]'' path after donating his eye to a beggar who threw the eye on the ground.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=416-417}}[[File:Lotus Sutra (Chokokan).jpg|thumb|Japanese depiction of the Lotus Sutra, where \u015a\u0101riputra prompts the Buddha to preach.|alt=|left]]\u015a\u0101riputra plays a major role in the [[Heart Sutra]], where the teaching is directed at him. \u015a\u0101riputra prompts the teaching of the sutra by asking the Mahayana bodhisattva [[Avalokite\u015bvara]] how to practice [[Prajnaparamita|wisdom]].{{sfn|Lopez|1988|p=52}} Avalokite\u015bvara's response to \u015a\u0101riputra, then makes up the body of the sutra.{{sfn|Lopez|1988|p=49}} When Avalokite\u015bvara finishes the sutra the Buddha shows approval of the teaching, and \u015a\u0101riputra, Avalokite\u015bvara, and the audience then rejoice.{{sfn|Lopez|1988|p=121}} In the [[Saddharmapundarika|Lotus Sutra]], the Buddha starts talking about the higher wisdom of [[buddhas]] and his use of skillful means (Sanskrit: [[Up\u0101ya|''up\u0101ya'']]) to teach the Dharma, which leaves the arhats in the assembly confused.{{sfn|Lopez|2016|p=12-13}} \u015a\u0101riputra then asks the Buddha to explain his teachings for the benefit of other beings, prompting the Buddha to teach the ''Lotus Sutra''.{{sfn|Hanh|2008|p=38}}  Later in the sutra, the Buddha explains that \u015a\u0101riputra had followed the [[bodhisattva]] path in past lives but had forgotten and followed the ''\u015ar\u0101vaka'' path in this life.{{sfn|Hanh|2008|p=46}} The Buddha then assures \u015a\u0101riputra that he will also achieve buddhahood and declares that \u015a\u0101riputra will become the future Buddha Padmaprabha.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=416-417}}{{sfn|Hanh|2008|p=47}} In the listing of the great arhats in the assembly at the beginning of the [[Longer Sukh\u0101vat\u012bvy\u016bha S\u016btra]], \u015a\u0101riputra is mentioned as the fifteenth of the great arhats, while in the [[Shorter Sukh\u0101vat\u012bvy\u016bha S\u016btra]] he is placed as the first.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=491}}\n\n== Relics ==\n{{Main|Relics of Sariputta and Moggallana}}\n[[File:003 Front View (33709016166).jpg|thumb|One of the [[Sanchi]] stupas, where relics of \u015a\u0101riputra were excavated.]]\nAccording to accounts from 7th century Chinese pilgrim [[Xuanzang]], \u015a\u0101riputra's as well as Maudgaly\u0101yana's relics could be found in the Indian city of [[Mathura]] in stupas built by King [[Asoka]].{{sfn|Higham|2004|p=215}} However, as of 1999, no archaeological reports have confirmed such findings at the sites mentioned by either Chinese pilgrims or Buddhist texts.{{sfn|Daulton|1999|p=104-105}} In 1851, archaeologist [[Alexander Cunningham]] and Lieutenant Fred. C. Maisey discovered a pair of sandstone boxes with encased bone fragments inside during an excavation of one of the [[Sanchi Stupa|stupas]] in the city of [[Sanchi Town|Sanchi]], with \u015a\u0101riputra's and Maudgaly\u0101yana's names inscribed on them.{{sfn|Daulton|1999|p=106-107}} \u015a\u0101riputra's casket contained pieces of [[sandalwood]], which Cunningham believed was part of \u015a\u0101riputra's [[funeral pyre]].{{sfn|Brekke|2007|p=274}} Another excavation by Cunningham and Maisey at st\u016bpas in the nearby town of [[Satdh\u0101ra]] found another pair of caskets with encased bone fragments with the two chief disciples' names inscribed.{{sfn|Daulton|1999|p=106-107}} Cunningham concluded that the relics were enshrined in stupas near Rajagaha after the disciples' deaths until the time of King Asoka, who then redistributed them in stupas throughout India.{{sfn|Brekke|2007|p=275}} Scholars have also theorized that a [[Shunga Empire|Sunga]] king may have redistributed the relics of the Buddha and his leading disciples and built stupas such as the one in Sanchi to enshrine them.{{sfn|Daulton|1999|p=105-106}}\n\nCunningham and Maisey later divided their findings among each other, with Maisey bringing the Satdh\u0101ra relics to Britain and eventually loaning them to the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] in London in 1866.{{sfn|Daulton|1999|p=108}}{{sfn|Brekke|2007|p=277}} The relics were eventually purchased by the Museum in 1921 from Maisley's son.{{sfn|Daulton|1999|p=108}} Cunningham brought his findings to Britain on two ships, one of which sank, thus the Sanchi relics are believed to have been lost.{{sfn|Daulton|1999|p=108}}{{sfn|Brekke|2007|p=277-278}} However, historian Torkel Brekke argues that Maisey took all the relics with him, and thus the Sanchi relics went to Britian along with the Satdh\u0101ra ones.{{sfn|Brekke|2007|p=277}} In the early 20th century, Buddhist organizations in India and Burma began pressuring the British government to return the relics to India, where they can be properly venerated. The British government conceded and transferred the relics to predominantly Buddhist [[Sri Lanka]] in 1947 in accordance with an agreement made with Buddhist organizations. In 1949, the relics were sent to India where they were put on tour around northern India before being enshrined in Sanchi in 1952.{{sfn|Daulton|1999|p=110-111}} In 1950, the relics were sent on tour to Burma, with Burmese Prime Minister [[U Nu]] later asking India for a portion of the relics. Indian Prime Minister [[Nehru]] agreed to make a \"permanent loan\" of a portion of the relics to Burma where they were enshrined in the [[Kaba Aye Pagoda]] in 1952.{{sfn|Daulton|1999|p=111-121}} Sri Lanka also obtained a portion of the relics, which were brought from Sanchi in 1952 and kept at the [[Maha Bodhi Society]] in Sri Lanka.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://catholicphilly.com/2015/01/news/world-news/buddhist-center-breaks-tradition-shows-pope-revered-relic/|title=Buddhist center breaks tradition, shows pope revered relic|last=Akkara|first=Anto|date=|website=Catholic Philly|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\n[[File:BACC - Bangkok - 2017-11-02 (008).jpg|thumb|Image of the Buddha with his chief disciples at [[Bangkok Art and Culture Centre]]. \u015a\u0101riputra is traditionally depicted on the right side of the Buddha while Maudgaly\u0101yana is traditionally depicted on the left.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=410}} |alt=]]\nAs the chief disciple of the Buddha, \u015a\u0101riputra is considered to be a particularly important figure in Buddhism, especially in the [[Theravada]] tradition. According to Buddhist academic [[Reginald Ray]], \u015a\u0101riputra was the greatest [[arhat]] in the [[P\u0101li Canon|Pali Canon]] and is ranked in the canon as being close to a second Buddha.{{sfn|Ray|1994|p=131-133}} In one text, he is referred to as \"King of the Dharma\" (Sanskrit: ''Dharmaraja'') a title generally reserved for the Buddha, and is described in several texts as one who \"spins the wheel of the Dharma\", a prerogative generally associated with Buddhas.{{sfn|Migot|1954|p=412, 500-501}} In the Pali Canon, \u015a\u0101riputra is credited as the main expounder of several [[suttas]], due to the Buddha trusting in his profound teaching ability.{{sfn|Wayman|1997|p=212}} Indologist [[Alex Wayman]] describes \u015a\u0101riputra as being exemplary of the four [[Brahmavihara|brahma-vih\u0101r\u0101s]], and credits these virtues with why the Buddha entrusted him with leadership of the Sangha.{{sfn|Wayman|1997|p=212}}\n\nIn [[Buddhist art]], he is often depicted alongside the Buddha and Maudgaly\u0101yana, with \u015a\u0101riputra usually depicted on the Buddha's right hand side and Maudgaly\u0101yana usually depicted on the Buddha's left hand side.{{sfn|Silk|2019|p=410}} According to Nyanaponika Thera, this imagery symbolizes the relative positions they held in life, with \u015a\u0101riputra being the Buddha's right hand monk.{{sfn|Hecker|Nyanaponika Thera|2003|p=47}} In Burma, \u015a\u0101riputra is believed to grant wisdom to worshippers, and is one of eight arhats commonly shown devotion to in protective rituals.{{sfn|Buswell|2004|p=750}}\n\n\u015a\u0101riputra is notable for being representative of scholarship and settled monasticism, rather than the forest Buddhism that most of the Buddha's [[Ten Principal Disciples|principal disciples]] are associated with.{{sfn|Ray|1994|p=131-133}} Migot, however, identifies texts that exclude \u015a\u0101riputra's scholastic character as the earliest sources, Migot goes on to argue that the historic \u015a\u0101riputra was different than the person preserved in the Pali Canon.{{sfn|Ray|1994|p=131-133}}{{sfn|Findly|2003|p=398}} According to Ray it is possible \u015a\u0101riputra's scholastic character was the result of texts that were added later, but states there is insufficient evidence to conclude to this.{{sfn|Ray|1994|p=134-136}}\n==See also==\n* [[Maudgalyayana|Moggall\u0101na]]\n*[[Khema]]\n*[[Pa\u00f1\u00f1\u0101]]\n* ''[[Sammaditthi Sutta]]'' \u2013 a Pali Canon discourse attributed to S\u0101riputta\n* [[Sariputra in the Jatakas]]\n* [[Sanchi]]\n* [[Bhadda Kundalakesa]], a former Jain ascetic converted to Buddhism by S\u0101riputta\n\n== Notes ==\n<references group=\"note\" responsive=\"1\"></references>\n\n== Citations ==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin |30em}}\n* {{Citation|last=Brekke|first=Torkel|date=2007-01-01|title=Bones of Contention: Buddhist Relics, Nationalism and the Politics of Archaeology|url=https://brill.com/view/journals/nu/54/3/article-p270_2.xml|journal=Numen|language=en|volume=54|issue=3|pages=270\u2013303|doi=10.1163/156852707X211564|issn=1568-5276}}\n* {{Citation|last1=Berger |first1=Patricia Ann |title=Latter Days of the Law: Images of Chinese Buddhism, 850 - 1850 ; [exhibition, August 27 - October 9 1994 ...] |date=1994 |publisher=University of Hawaii Press |isbn=978-0-8248-1662-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y6ffYIPn--wC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&source=gbs_navlinks_s |language=en}}\n* {{Citation|last1=Bodhi |first1=Bhikkhu |last2=Dhamma |first2=Rewata |title=A comprehensive manual of Abhidhamma : the Abhidhammattha sangaha of \u0100cariya Anuruddha |date=1993 |publisher=BPS Pariyatti Edition |isbn=978-1-928706-02-1 |edition=1st BPS Pariyatti}}\n* {{Citation|last1=Buswell|first1=Robert E. Jr.|title=Encyclopedia of Buddhism|date=2004|url=http://www.ahandfulofleaves.org/documents/Encyclopedia%20of%20Buddhism_2%20Vols_%20Buswell.pdf|location=New York, NY|publisher=Macmillan Reference, USA|isbn=0-02-865718-7}}\n* {{Citation|last1=Buswell|first1=Robert E. Jr.|title=Princeton Dictionary of Buddhism.|date=2013|url=http://www.daophatngaynay.com/vn/files/file-nen/Princeton_Dictionary_of_Buddhism_890707662.pdf|location=Princeton, NJ|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|isbn=978-0-691-15786-3|last2=Lopez|first2=Donald S. Jr.|author2-link=Donald S. Lopez Jr.}}\n* {{Citation|last1=Carus|first1=Paul|title=Ashvajit's Stanza and Its Significance|date=1905|url=http://opensiuc.lib.siu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1862&context=ocj|journal=[[Open Court Publishing Company|Ope