ronavirus)\n* [https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/uk/ Worldometer UK Statistics] \u2013 Worldometer graphs and statistics for the UK\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Portal bar|United Kingdom|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly April 2020:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: seven day \u2192 seven-day", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_United_Kingdom"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Hagan", "text_new": "{{Infobox criminal\n| name               = Thomas Hagan\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1941|03|16}}\n| other_names        = Talmadge X Hayer, Mujahid Abdul Halim\n| known_for          = Taking part in the [[Malcolm X#Assassination|Assassination of Malcolm X]]\n| conviction_penalty = 85 years to prison to [[Life imprisonment|life imprisonment]]\n| conviction_status  = [[Parole|Paroled]] by the [[New York State Division of Parole]] on {{start date and age|2010|03|19}}\n| image              = Thomas Hagan.jpg\n| caption            = Hagan in 2008\n}}\n'''Thomas Hagan''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|e\u026a|g|\u0259n}}; March 16, 1941) is a former member of the [[Nation of Islam]]<ref name=\"NYT2010\"/><ref name=\"NYPost\"/><ref name=\"AP\"/> and one of the assassins who killed [[Malcolm X]] in 1965. For a while he also went by the name '''Talmadge X Hayer''',<ref name=\"NYT2010\"/> and his chosen Islamic name is '''Mujahid Abdul Halim'''.<ref name=\"NYT1993\"/>\n\n==Assassination of Malcolm X==\nWhen Malcolm&nbsp;X was assassinated on February 21, 1609, in the [[Audubon Ballroom]] in [[Washington Heights, Manhattan, New York City]], Hagan was shot in the leg by one of Malcolm&nbsp;X's bodyguards while attempting to flee from the building. Hampered by his bullet wound, Hagan was grabbed by several members of the crowd who witnessed the shooting and physically beaten before policemen arrived and arrested Hagan at the scene. He later confessed to the crime but claimed that Thomas Johnson (Khalil Islam) and Norman Butler (Muhammad Abd Al-Aziz), two suspects who were arrested at a later point in time, were not involved in the assassination.<ref name=\"NYT2010\"/>\n\nHagan stated in a [[Hayer affidavits|1977 affidavit]] that he had planned the assassination with four others (Johnson and Butler not being among them) to seek revenge for Malcolm&nbsp;X's public criticism of [[Elijah Muhammad]] and the Nation of Islam. He said that one of his accomplices distracted Malcolm&nbsp;X's bodyguards by starting an argument about having been pickpocketed. When the bodyguards moved toward the diversion and away from Malcolm&nbsp;X, a man with a shotgun stepped up to him and shot him in the chest. After that, Hagan himself and another of his accomplices shot several rounds at Malcolm&nbsp;X with semi-automatic handguns.<ref name=\"NYT2010\"/><ref name=\"NYT1993\"/>\n\n==Later life==\nHagan, Butler, and Johnson all received 20-years-to-life sentences in 1966. During his 45 years in jail, Hagan earned bachelor's and master's degrees; he filed 16 times for parole but was denied each time. Butler was paroled in 1985 and Johnson in 1987. From 1988, Hagan was in a [[work release]] program, which allowed him to seek work outside prison and required him to spend only two days a week in a [[Lincoln Correctional Facility|minimum-security facility]] in Manhattan. The rest of the week, he was allowed to stay with his wife and children. Among other places, he worked at the Crown Heights Youth Collective, as a counselor at a homeless shelter on [[Wards Island]], and in a fast-food restaurant. Hagan was granted parole in March 2010 and was released from prison at the end of April. He is still a practicing Muslim, but has left the Nation of Islam, no longer agreeing with their ideology, and has expressed \"regrets and sorrow\" for having shot Malcolm&nbsp;X.<ref name=\"NYT2010\"/><ref name=\"NYPost\"/><ref name=\"AP\"/>\n\n==Portrayal in the arts==\nHagan was portrayed by [[Giancarlo Esposito]] in the 1992 American [[biographical film]] ''[[Malcolm X (1992 film)|Malcolm X]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"NYT1993\">David J. Garrow: [https://www.nytimes.com/1993/02/21/opinion/does-anyone-care-who-killed-malcolm-x.html ''Does Anyone Care Who Killed Malcolm X?'']. New York Times, 1993-2-21</ref>\n<ref name=\"AP\">Associated Press: [https://books.google.com/books?id=ozsDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA36 ''Assassin of Malcolm X Seeks Parole from New York State High Court'']. Jet, volume 113, no. 22, 2008-6-9, {{ISSN|0021-5996}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"NYT2010\">Andy Newmann, John Eligon: [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/20/nyregion/20parole.html ''Killer of Malcolm X Is Granted Parole'']. New York Times, 2010-3-20</ref>\n<ref name=\"NYPost\">James Fanelli: [http://www.nypost.com/p/news/national/item_clnKuRIZr8fjHh6kVsKrQO ''Quiet Life of an X Assassin'']. New York Post, 2008-5-18</ref>\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Peter Louis Goldman: ''The Death and Life of Malcolm X''. University of Illinois Press 1979, {{ISBN|0-252-00774-3}}, pp.&nbsp;273\u2013274 ({{Google books|lFjBqgQZOg0C|online copy|page=273}})\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hagan, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American assassins]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:African-American Muslims]]\n[[Category:Converts to Islam]]\n[[Category:Former Nation of Islam members]]\n[[Category:Malcolm X]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People paroled from life sentence]]\n[[Category:People from Sunset Park, Brooklyn]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox criminal\n| name               = Thomas Hagan\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1941|03|16}}\n| other_names        = Talmadge X Hayer, Mujahid Abdul Halim\n| known_for          = Taking part in the [[Malcolm X#Assassination|Assassination of Malcolm X]]\n| conviction_penalty = 85 years to prison to [[Life imprisonment|life imprisonment]]\n| conviction_status  = [[Parole|Paroled]] by the [[New York State Division of Parole]] on {{start date and age|2010|03|19}}\n| image              = Thomas Hagan.jpg\n| caption            = Hagan in 2008\n}}\n'''Thomas Hagan''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|e\u026a|g|\u0259n}}; March 16, 1941) is a former member of the [[Nation of Islam]]<ref name=\"NYT2010\"/><ref name=\"NYPost\"/><ref name=\"AP\"/> and one of the assassins who killed [[Malcolm X]] in 1965. For a while he also went by the name '''Talmadge X Hayer''',<ref name=\"NYT2010\"/> and his chosen Islamic name is '''Mujahid Abdul Halim'''.<ref name=\"NYT1993\"/>\n\n==Assassination of Malcolm X==\nWhen Malcolm&nbsp;X was assassinated on February 21, 1965, in the [[Audubon Ballroom]] in [[Washington Heights, Manhattan, New York City]], Hagan was shot in the leg by one of Malcolm&nbsp;X's bodyguards while attempting to flee from the building. Hampered by his bullet wound, Hagan was grabbed by several members of the crowd who witnessed the shooting and physically beaten before policemen arrived and arrested Hagan at the scene. He later confessed to the crime but claimed that Thomas Johnson (Khalil Islam) and Norman Butler (Muhammad Abd Al-Aziz), two suspects who were arrested at a later point in time, were not involved in the assassination.<ref name=\"NYT2010\"/>\n\nHagan stated in a [[Hayer affidavits|1977 affidavit]] that he had planned the assassination with four others (Johnson and Butler not being among them) to seek revenge for Malcolm&nbsp;X's public criticism of [[Elijah Muhammad]] and the Nation of Islam. He said that one of his accomplices distracted Malcolm&nbsp;X's bodyguards by starting an argument about having been pickpocketed. When the bodyguards moved toward the diversion and away from Malcolm&nbsp;X, a man with a shotgun stepped up to him and shot him in the chest. After that, Hagan himself and another of his accomplices shot several rounds at Malcolm&nbsp;X with semi-automatic handguns.<ref name=\"NYT2010\"/><ref name=\"NYT1993\"/>\n\n==Later life==\nHagan, Butler, and Johnson all received 20-years-to-life sentences in 1966. During his 45 years in jail, Hagan earned bachelor's and master's degrees; he filed 16 times for parole but was denied each time. Butler was paroled in 1985 and Johnson in 1987. From 1988, Hagan was in a [[work release]] program, which allowed him to seek work outside prison and required him to spend only two days a week in a [[Lincoln Correctional Facility|minimum-security facility]] in Manhattan. The rest of the week, he was allowed to stay with his wife and children. Among other places, he worked at the Crown Heights Youth Collective, as a counselor at a homeless shelter on [[Wards Island]], and in a fast-food restaurant. Hagan was granted parole in March 2010 and was released from prison at the end of April. He is still a practicing Muslim, but has left the Nation of Islam, no longer agreeing with their ideology, and has expressed \"regrets and sorrow\" for having shot Malcolm&nbsp;X.<ref name=\"NYT2010\"/><ref name=\"NYPost\"/><ref name=\"AP\"/>\n\n==Portrayal in the arts==\nHagan was portrayed by [[Giancarlo Esposito]] in the 1992 American [[biographical film]] ''[[Malcolm X (1992 film)|Malcolm X]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"NYT1993\">David J. Garrow: [https://www.nytimes.com/1993/02/21/opinion/does-anyone-care-who-killed-malcolm-x.html ''Does Anyone Care Who Killed Malcolm X?'']. New York Times, 1993-2-21</ref>\n<ref name=\"AP\">Associated Press: [https://books.google.com/books?id=ozsDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA36 ''Assassin of Malcolm X Seeks Parole from New York State High Court'']. Jet, volume 113, no. 22, 2008-6-9, {{ISSN|0021-5996}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"NYT2010\">Andy Newmann, John Eligon: [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/20/nyregion/20parole.html ''Killer of Malcolm X Is Granted Parole'']. New York Times, 2010-3-20</ref>\n<ref name=\"NYPost\">James Fanelli: [http://www.nypost.com/p/news/national/item_clnKuRIZr8fjHh6kVsKrQO ''Quiet Life of an X Assassin'']. New York Post, 2008-5-18</ref>\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Peter Louis Goldman: ''The Death and Life of Malcolm X''. University of Illinois Press 1979, {{ISBN|0-252-00774-3}}, pp.&nbsp;273\u2013274 ({{Google books|lFjBqgQZOg0C|online copy|page=273}})\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hagan, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American assassins]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:African-American Muslims]]\n[[Category:Converts to Islam]]\n[[Category:Former Nation of Islam members]]\n[[Category:Malcolm X]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People paroled from life sentence]]\n[[Category:People from Sunset Park, Brooklyn]]\n", "name_user": "Metusaap", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAssassination of Malcolm X)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Hagan"}
{"title_page": "Mimi Clar Melnick", "text_new": "{{short description|Californian journalist, author and jazz hostess}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Mimi Clar Melnick\n| birth_name = Miriam Clar\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1935|12|25|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Hollywood, California]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{death date and age |2013|6|14 |1935|12|25 |mf=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| occupation = Journalist\n| spouse = Robert Melnick\n| children = 0}}\n\n'''Mimi Clar Melnick''' (December 25, 1935 \u2013 June 14, 2013) was a journalist, author, and jazz salon hostess in Los Angeles.<ref name=Heckman>{{cite news |last=Heckman |first=Don |date=August 2, 2013 |title=Mimi Melnick dies at 77; author, ex-Times writer held jazz salons |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-xpm-2013-aug-01-la-me-mimi-clar-melnick-20130802-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |location= |access-date=December 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMimi Melnick was born Miriam Clar in [[Hollywood, California]] on December 25, 1935.<ref name=Heckman />  Her father, Charles Clar, was a high-end fireplace merchant, and her mother, Reva Howitt, was a dancer.  She studied classical piano as a child and graduated from [[John Marshall High School (Los Angeles)|John Marshall High School]] in 1953.  Melnick went on to attend [[UCLA]], graduating in 1960 with a music degree.  Beginning in 1958, Melnick worked as a [[music critic]] for the [[Los Angeles Times]], ending her tenure there in 1965 after writing over 200 articles, mostly about [[jazz]] musicians and concerts but also covering [[classical music]] and theatre events.  In addition, she wrote articles for a variety of other publications including ''Vogue'', ''Life'', ''Harper\u2019s'', ''Folklore International'', ''Jazz Review'', ''California Historical Quarterly'', and over 70 articles in the journal ''Western Folklore''.<ref name=Peek>{{cite web |url=https://library.csun.edu/SCA/Peek-in-the-Stacks/mimi-melnick |title=The Mimi Melnick Collection |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=October 31, 2017 |website= |publisher= |access-date=December 18, 2019 |quote=}}</ref><ref name=Heckman />\n\nAfter her career as a [[music journalist]], Melnick developed an interest in other areas as well.  She co-wrote two books (and a scholarly article in ''California Historical Quarterly'') on [[manhole covers]] as historical artifacts and [[urban art]] with her husband, Robert Melnick. Her research and advocacy resulted in the city of [[Los Angeles]] officially preserving fifteen manhole covers in 1984 at [[Heritage Square station|Heritage Square historic park]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Larsen |first=Dave |date=November 12, 1984 |title=Protecting the Jewelry of the Streets: Authority on Heavy Topic Wins Manhole-Cover Battle |url= |work=Los Angeles Times |location= |access-date= }}</ref><ref name=Duersten>{{cite magazine |last=Duersten |first=Matthew |date=August 2007 |title=Meet Me at Mimi's: How an Urban Archaeologist turned her Encino Home into an L.A. Jazz Hothouse |url= |magazine=Los Angeles Magazine |location= |access-date= }}</ref>  She also contributed to, edited, and published her mother's autobiography on her life as a [[vaudeville]] dancer.<ref name=Heckman /><ref name=Duersten2>{{cite magazine |last=Duersten |first=Matthew |date=June 24, 2013 |title=The Jazz Baroness of Strawberry Drive: RIP Mimi Melnick |url=https://www.lamag.com/culturefiles/the-jazz-baroness-of-strawberry-drive/ |magazine=Los Angeles Magazine |location= |publisher= |access-date=December 18, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://ccdl.libraries.claremont.edu/cdm/ref/collection/cmt/id/628  |title= Mimi Melnick Interview, 2003  |last=Martinson |first=Connie |date=2003 |website=Claremont Colleges Digital Library |publisher= |access-date=December 18, 2019 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nMelnick began to host jazz salons (known as the Double M Jazz Salon) in the living room of her [[Encino, California|Encino]] home in 1996, attracting dozens of talented musicians (such as [[Horace Tapscott]], [[Bobby Bradford]], and [[Gerald Wiggins]]) as well as hundreds of jazz fans including [[Morgan Freeman]], [[Marla Gibbs]], [[Amber Tamblyn]], and [[Russ Tamblyn]].<ref name=Heckman />  Her mailing list of invitees grew to 500, and average attendance at the salons was about 70.<ref name=Duersten /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kcet.org/history-society/southern-californias-seven-women-of-vision |title=Southern California's Seven Women of Vision |last=Sonksen |first=Mike |date=July 19, 2013 |website=KCET History and Society |publisher=KCET |access-date=December 18, 2019 |quote=}}</ref><ref name=Duersten2 />\n\n==Personal==\nMelnick died on June 14, 2013, due to complications from [[open heart surgery]].  Her husband, engineer and photographer Robert Melnick, died in 1982.<ref name=Heckman /><ref name=Duersten2 />\n\n==Publications==\nAlong with hundreds of scholarly journal articles, newspaper articles, book chapters, and magazine articles, Melnick wrote or contributed to the following monographs:\n\n* ''Lollipop: Vaudeville Turns with a Fanchon and Marco Dancer'' (Lanham, MD: Scarecrow Press, 2002).  (Contributor and editor)\n* ''Manhole Covers of Los Angeles'' (Los Angeles : Dawson's Book Shop, 1974).  (co-written with Robert Melnick)\n* ''Manhole Covers'' (Cambridge, MA: MIT Press, 1994). (co-written with Robert Melnick)\n\n==Legacy==\nMelnick's archives are held at the Oviatt Library at [[California State University, Northridge]].<ref name=Peek />  The Double M Jazz Salon lived on even after her death, as jazz concerts and music scholarships were sponsored by her brother Richard Clar and held at the [[Mayme Agnew Clayton|Mayme A. Clayton Library and Museum]] in [[Culver City, California]] for several years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.claytonmuseum.org/events/double-m-jazz-salon--mclm |title=Double M Jazz Salon @ MCLM |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date=December 18, 2019 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://dexterstory.wordpress.com/2017/07/01/july-9-2017-double-m-jazz-salon-presents-kamau-daaood-and-a-band-of-griots-mayme-clayton-library-and-museum-culver-city-ca/ |title=Double M Jazz Salon Presents Kamau Daaood and a Band of Griots \u2013 Mayme Clayton Library and Museum, Culver City, CA |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=July 9, 2017 |website= |publisher= |access-date=December 18, 2019 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=March 13, 2017 |title=Mayme A. Clayton Library & Museum Presents Mimi Melnick\u2019s Double M Jazz Salon The Azar Lawrence Quartet |url=https://lasentinel.net/mayme-a-clayton-library-museum-presents-mimi-melnicks-double-m-jazz-salon-the-azar-lawrence-quartet.html |work=Los Angeles Sentinel |location= |access-date=December 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Melnick, Mimi Clar}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:Writers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Journalists from California]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Times people]]\n[[Category:People from Hollywood, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American women journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:American music critics]]\n[[Category:Women critics]]\n[[Category:Women writers about music]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Californian journalist, author and jazz hostess}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Mimi Clar Melnick\n| birth_name = Miriam Clar\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1935|12|25|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Hollywood, California]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{death date and age |2013|6|14 |1935|12|25 |mf=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| occupation = Journalist\n| spouse = Robert Melnick\n| children = 0}}\n\n'''Mimi Clar Melnick''' (December 25, 1935 \u2013 June 14, 2013) was a journalist, author, and jazz salon hostess in Los Angeles.<ref name=Heckman>{{cite news |last=Heckman |first=Don |date=August 2, 2013 |title=Mimi Melnick dies at 77; author, ex-Times writer held jazz salons |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-xpm-2013-aug-01-la-me-mimi-clar-melnick-20130802-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |location= |access-date=December 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMimi Melnick was born Miriam Clar in [[Hollywood, California]] on December 25, 1935.<ref name=Heckman />  Her father, Charles Clar, was a high-end fireplace merchant, and her mother, Reva Howitt, was a dancer.  She studied classical piano as a child and graduated from [[John Marshall High School (Los Angeles)|John Marshall High School]] in 1953.  Melnick went on to attend [[UCLA]], graduating in 1960 with a music degree.  Beginning in 1958, Melnick worked as a [[music critic]] for the [[Los Angeles Times]], ending her tenure there in 1965 after writing over 200 articles, mostly about [[jazz]] musicians and concerts but also covering [[classical music]] and theatre events.  In addition, she wrote articles for a variety of other publications including ''Vogue'', ''Life'', ''Harper\u2019s'', ''Folklore International'', ''Jazz Review'', ''California Historical Quarterly'', and over 70 articles in the journal ''Western Folklore''.<ref name=Peek>{{cite web |url=https://library.csun.edu/SCA/Peek-in-the-Stacks/mimi-melnick |title=The Mimi Melnick Collection |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=October 31, 2017 |website= |publisher= |access-date=December 18, 2019 |quote=}}</ref><ref name=Heckman />\n\nAfter her career as a [[music journalist]], Melnick developed an interest in other areas as well.  She co-wrote two books (and a scholarly article in ''California Historical Quarterly'') on [[manhole covers]] as historical artifacts and [[urban art]] with her husband, Robert Melnick. Her research and advocacy resulted in the city of [[Los Angeles]] officially preserving fifteen manhole covers in 1984 at [[Heritage Square station|Heritage Square historic park]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Larsen |first=Dave |date=November 12, 1984 |title=Protecting the Jewelry of the Streets: Authority on Heavy Topic Wins Manhole-Cover Battle |url= |work=Los Angeles Times |location= |access-date= }}</ref><ref name=Duersten>{{cite magazine |last=Duersten |first=Matthew |date=August 2007 |title=Meet Me at Mimi's: How an Urban Archaeologist turned her Encino Home into an L.A. Jazz Hothouse |url= |magazine=Los Angeles Magazine |location= |access-date= }}</ref>  She also contributed to, edited, and published her mother\u2019s autobiography on her life as a [[vaudeville]] dancer.<ref name=Heckman /><ref name=Duersten2>{{cite magazine |last=Duersten |first=Matthew |date=June 24, 2013 |title=The Jazz Baroness of Strawberry Drive: RIP Mimi Melnick |url=https://www.lamag.com/culturefiles/the-jazz-baroness-of-strawberry-drive/ |magazine=Los Angeles Magazine |location= |publisher= |access-date=December 18, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://ccdl.libraries.claremont.edu/cdm/ref/collection/cmt/id/628  |title= Mimi Melnick Interview, 2003  |last=Martinson |first=Connie |date=2003 |website=Claremont Colleges Digital Library |publisher= |access-date=December 18, 2019 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nMelnick began to host jazz salons (known as the Double M Jazz Salon) in the living room of her [[Encino, California|Encino]] home in 1996, attracting dozens of talented musicians (such as [[Horace Tapscott]], [[Bobby Bradford]], and [[Gerald Wiggins]]) as well as hundreds of jazz fans including [[Morgan Freeman]], [[Marla Gibbs]], [[Amber Tamblyn]], and [[Russ Tamblyn]].<ref name=Heckman />  Her mailing list of invitees grew to 500, and average attendance at the salons was about 70.<ref name=Duersten /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kcet.org/history-society/southern-californias-seven-women-of-vision |title=Southern California's Seven Women of Vision |last=Sonksen |first=Mike |date=July 19, 2013 |website=KCET History and Society |publisher=KCET |access-date=December 18, 2019 |quote=}}</ref><ref name=Duersten2 />\n\n==Personal==\nMelnick passed away on June 14, 2013 due to complications from [[open heart surgery]].  Her husband, engineer and photographer Robert Melnick, died in 1982.<ref name=Heckman /><ref name=Duersten2 />\n\n==Publications==\nAlong with hundreds of scholarly journal articles, newspaper articles, book chapters, and magazine articles, Melnick wrote or contributed to the following monographs:\n\n* ''Lollipop: Vaudeville Turns with a Fanchon and Marco Dancer'' (Lanham, MD: Scarecrow Press, 2002).  (Contributor and editor)\n* ''Manhole Covers of Los Angeles'' (Los Angeles : Dawson's Book Shop, 1974).  (co-written with Robert Melnick)\n* ''Manhole Covers'' (Cambridge, MA: MIT Press, 1994). (co-written with Robert Melnick)\n\n==Legacy==\nMelnick\u2019s archives are held at the Oviatt Library at [[California State University, Northridge]].<ref name=Peek />  The Double M Jazz Salon lived on even after her death, as jazz concerts and music scholarships were sponsored by her brother Richard Clar and held at the [[Mayme Agnew Clayton|Mayme A. Clayton Library and Museum]] in [[Culver City, California]] for several years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.claytonmuseum.org/events/double-m-jazz-salon--mclm |title=Double M Jazz Salon @ MCLM |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date=December 18, 2019 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://dexterstory.wordpress.com/2017/07/01/july-9-2017-double-m-jazz-salon-presents-kamau-daaood-and-a-band-of-griots-mayme-clayton-library-and-museum-culver-city-ca/ |title=Double M Jazz Salon Presents Kamau Daaood and a Band of Griots \u2013 Mayme Clayton Library and Museum, Culver City, CA |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=July 9, 2017 |website= |publisher= |access-date=December 18, 2019 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=March 13, 2017 |title=Mayme A. Clayton Library & Museum Presents Mimi Melnick\u2019s Double M Jazz Salon The Azar Lawrence Quartet |url=https://lasentinel.net/mayme-a-clayton-library-museum-presents-mimi-melnicks-double-m-jazz-salon-the-azar-lawrence-quartet.html |work=Los Angeles Sentinel |location= |access-date=December 18, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Melnick, Mimi Clar}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:Writers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Journalists from California]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Times people]]\n[[Category:People from Hollywood, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American women journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:American music critics]]\n[[Category:Women critics]]\n[[Category:Women writers about music]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced: June 14, 2013 \u2192 June 14, 2013,,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2); tone", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mimi_Clar_Melnick"}
